<HEAD>Blood Bank Held Responsible for Transfusion-Related AIDS Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER McNULTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A jury found a blood bank negligent Thursday for improperly screening its blood in the case of a 5 -LCB- - year-old boy who contracted AIDS through a transfusion, a verdict believed to be the first of its kind, lawyers said `` We just feel this is a great moral victory. I think the blood industry, particularly in high-risk areas like <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>, has got to shape up,'' said <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Osborn </PERSON>, whose son, <PERSON> Michael </PERSON>, was the plaintiff in the case. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON>, who has a brain tumor and lymphoma, was diagnosed with acquired immune deficiency syndrome in September 1987. He has only a few months to live, said the Osborns' lawyer, <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Moriarty </PERSON>. `` At least <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> will be around in some way in the future. At least his name will not be forgotten,'' added Mrs. <PERSON> Osborn </PERSON>. The jury found <ORGANIZATION> Irwin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Memorial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Blood </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> San </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Francisco </ORGANIZATION>, which supplies blood to about 40 hospitals, to be negligent in failing to screen the blood adequately, although some AIDS screening was done at the facility at the time. In addition, the jury ruled that the blood bank erred in not allowing family members to target their blood donations for <PERSON> Michael </PERSON>. <PERSON> Moriarty </PERSON> said the blood bank had rejected requests by the boy's family and friends to donate blood for the transfusion, saying they had no policy to accommodate such requests when in fact they did The blood bank's attorney, <PERSON> Duncan </PERSON> <PERSON> Barr </PERSON>, denied that the blood bank acted negligently and said the decision will be appealed. The jury awarded the <LOCATION> Sacramento </LOCATION> family $ 550,000 in compensatory damages. The child, suffering from a congenital heart defect, received the transfusion Feb. 24, 1983, when he was three weeks old. The boy's parents were awarded $ 200,000 to pay for past and future medical bills but were denied any damages for pain and suffering. The jury voted unanimously to award the damages and split 9-3 on the question of liability, said <PERSON> Moriarty </PERSON>. Defending <PERSON> Irwin </PERSON>'s decisions in the case, <PERSON> Barr </PERSON> said in 1983 the blood bank had a policy of allowing so-called directed donors only for medical reasons, such as blood donations from organ donors. <PERSON> Barr </PERSON> and Dr. <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Asher </PERSON>, founder and chairman of <ORGANIZATION> HemaCare </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, a private blood bank in <LOCATION> Sherman </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Oaks </LOCATION>, said the case was the first time a blood bank was found responsible for a transfusion-related AIDS case. A <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION> jury in June cleared a blood bank of liability in the case of a woman who contracted AIDS through a transfusion. A similar case in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> in 1986 ended in a settlement before the trial ended. AIDS is caused by a virus that damages the body's immune system, leaving victims susceptible to infections and cancer. It is spread most often through sexual contact, needles or syringes shared by drug abusers, infected blood or blood products, and from pregnant women to their offspring.
</TEXT>
