<HEAD>Mercury Astronaut Says U.S. Lags in Space Technology</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANNAPOLIS, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Wally </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Schirra </PERSON>, one of the first seven Mercury astronauts, says the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> no longer leads the world in space technology and should renew its commitment to space exploration. In an address at the <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Naval Academy Tuesday night, the former <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> captain called on the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration to make building a space station the top priority of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s space program. Such a station could serve as a port for manned and unmanned exploratory missions to other planets and their moons, said <PERSON> Schirra </PERSON>, 65. <PERSON> Schirra </PERSON>, a 1946 academy graduate who is now a business executive, wore a `` Beat Army'' pin _ the same message he carried on a placard during a 1965 Gemini mission. The annual <ORGANIZATION> Army-Navy </ORGANIZATION> football game is this weekend. <PERSON> Schirra </PERSON> said the Skylab project marked the beginning of the decline of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> space program. Budget cuts forced the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aeronautics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> to allow Skylab to break up in orbit and no serious financial commitment has been made since, he said. The former astronaut, speaking on the eve of the launching of the secret military shuttle <LOCATION> Atlantis </LOCATION>, said space shuttle missions have had `` no place to go. ... They were just supposed to go into outer space and come home. We did that 25 years ago.'' <PERSON> Schirra </PERSON> praised the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>'s space program for its long-range goals. The Soviets have done extensive research on how weightlessness affects humans and have worked to develop ships that can stay in orbit for years, but the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has attempted neither, he said. <PERSON> Schirra </PERSON> was selected as a Mercury astronaut in April 1959. In 1962, he became the fifth astronaut to fly in space.
