<HEAD>Visit to Tehran Gives Glimpses of a City of Contrasts</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Missing Iranians</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> is a city full of contrasts, showing the effects of war, tradition and modern lifestyles. An <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> correspondent accompanied West German Foreign Minister <PERSON> Hans-Dietrich </PERSON> <PERSON> Genscher </PERSON> on a recent visit, and here is his report:
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By DETLEF RUDEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEHRAN, Iran (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 In the bustle of <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION>'s main bazaar, young women wearing blue jeans under their traditional Islamic chador robes stroll past crippled war veterans hobbling on rickety wooden crutches between merchant stalls. A few blocks away, curious children and young people flock to gaze at the magnificent former residence of the late <PERSON> Shah </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>. Some people on the streets of <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> openly indicated their displeasure with <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s revolutionary government, which toppled the shah in 1979. A book vendor asked for an up-to-date city guidebook told a <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> reporter, `` There has been nothing like that since the revolution.'' The merchant then held up a tattered guidebook dating back before the Islamic revolution. She pointed to a photograph in the book of the shah's family. The picture had been crossed out with thick black censorship marks. `` It really is a shame,'' the book vendor said angrily. Journalists accompanying West German Foreign Minister <PERSON> Hans-Dietrich </PERSON> <PERSON> Genscher </PERSON> to <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> were not allowed to tour the city freely or take pictures during the three-day state visit that ended Tuesday. But the glimpses they were allowed showed <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> is a city full of contrasts. The Westerners witnessed clear evidence of Moslem fundamentalism, but also signs of modernism. <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> has been making efforts to increase its contacts with some Western nations, such as <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, as it tries to recover from its crippling eight-year war with <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> after a cease-fire. But West German businessmen who accompanied <PERSON> Genscher </PERSON> to <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> said it is still not certain whether <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s commitment to conservative Moslem principles will hinder efforts to build up the country. `` Whoever plans to invest here must carefully weigh each step,'' said <PERSON> Rochus-Ernst </PERSON> <PERSON> Freiherr </PERSON> <PERSON> von </PERSON> <PERSON> Luettwitz </PERSON>, a West German involved in business discussions with <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>. There are signs everywhere that a fundamentalist Islamic philosophy that has governed life in <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> since the <PERSON> shah </PERSON>'s ouster still holds sway. Iranian Revolutionary Guards carrying automatic rifles were plainly visible on <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION>'s streets, watching the <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> journalists to make sure they did not violate any of the restrictions under which their presence was permitted. The Iranian government's disdain for the late shah, who was friendly with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, becomes bitterly clear with a visit to the grand palace where he and his family had lived. Pictures of the shah have been turned upside-down inside the rooms of the palace, now a museum. Photographs showing poverty and squalor during the <PERSON> shah </PERSON>'s rule have been placed near tables exhibiting valuables once owned by the former ruler. Plaques tell visitors the purpose of rooms in the palace during the <PERSON> shah </PERSON>'s reign, but in a belittling fashion. `` Former Working Room of the Shah Who Fled,'' reads one plaque. But along with such clear evidence of Moslem fundamentalism, there are also signs <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION>'s people do not totally reject Western ways. Many of <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION>'s young women wear blue jeans or short skirts under their traditional black chador robes, the fabric pushed back just enough on their foreheads to reveal a lock or two of hair. Several young women were also wearing high-heeled shoes. <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> residents on the streets did not stare at the Western visitors but actually seemed to welcome them. There were also signs of the devastating war with <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>. Crippled young men hobbled along the streets and the Westerners saw empty lots where they were told bombed-out homes once stood. There are also signs of stymied progress within <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION>. Just behind the Hotel Esteghlal, called the Royal Tehran Hilton before the 1979 revolution, chickens raced among building materials at the site of an uncompleted structure. Rusty steel girders were scattered on the ground, giving the impression the structure had not been worked on for some time. Inside the hotel itself, the climate-control system was able to churn out only humid blasts of air. <PERSON> Genscher </PERSON> and his entourage were greeted with open arms by Iranian officials. But Western journalists were told through the West German Embassy that while in <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> they would be permitted to write only about <PERSON> Genscher </PERSON>'s meetings and that their visas were valid only for the duration of the official visit. In addition, it was made clear to <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> photographers that the Iranians would not allow pictures to be taken of life on <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION>'s streets
</TEXT>
