<HEAD>Lawsuit Expected As Smokescreen, Westinghouse Says</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 5 grafs to UPDATE with formal announcement of
lawsuit set; picks up 4th graf: ``What we're ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By EARL BOHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Westinghouse </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> said Wednesday it will not be a scapegoat for what it calls politically motivated opposition in the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> to a nuclear power plant it built under former President <PERSON> Ferdinand </PERSON> <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON>. <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> President <PERSON> Corazon </PERSON> <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> says the $ 2.3 billion plant 60 miles northwest of <LOCATION> Manila </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Bataan </LOCATION> province is unsafe in part because of its design and its location on an earthquake fault near a volcano. Her government has said it plans to sue <ORGANIZATION> Westinghouse </ORGANIZATION> for damages and breach of contract regarding the plant, which never went into operation because of alleged safety defects. Her legal adviser, <PERSON> Adolfo </PERSON> <PERSON> Azcuna </PERSON>, said in late October that a lawsuit was ready and likely would be filed within a month in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. An agreement barring either the government or the company from taking legal action was due to expire Thursday. Formal announcement of the lawsuit was scheduled Thursday in <LOCATION> Manila </LOCATION> for 2:30 p.m. -LRB- 1:30 a.m. EST -RRB- at the presidential palace. `` What we're finding here are the results of a political policy that came to life when they were running for office,'' said <PERSON> Nathaniel </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Woodson </PERSON>, general manager of the <ORGANIZATION> Westinghouse </ORGANIZATION> nuclear fuels unit. `` They now feel they have a political albatross around their neck and they're trying to blame us.'' The reactor's opponents also allege that bribes were paid over the awarding of the prime contract. `` We won fairly and squarly,'' <PERSON> Woodson </PERSON> said in an interview. <PERSON> Woodson </PERSON> and Deputy General Counsel <PERSON> Louis </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Briskman </PERSON> said that <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> officials have acknowledged during private talks that no matter how safe the plant is, they do n't intend to allow nuclear power production in the country. `` Safety has nothing to do with it,'' <PERSON> Woodson </PERSON> said. With all but $ 20 million to $ 30 million still due from <LOCATION> Manila </LOCATION> for the power plant, <ORGANIZATION> Westinghouse </ORGANIZATION> could walk away from the 10-year-old controversy, said <PERSON> Woodson </PERSON>. The bigger risk perhaps is damage to the company's international standing as a designer and builder of nuclear power plants. `` All over the world we have built plants, and we have n't had this problem. If they do n't want to operate this plant, that's they're decision, but do n't make <ORGANIZATION> Westinghouse </ORGANIZATION> a scapegoat,'' he said `` <ORGANIZATION> Westinghouse </ORGANIZATION> will not be a scapegoat.'' The company cited investigations by the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> that produced no evidence warranting charges. Further, a safety study commissioned by the Aquino government concluded that the plant is safe, <ORGANIZATION> Westinghouse </ORGANIZATION> said. A trade journal published a draft of that report. The government says the final report concludes otherwise, but officials have refused to release the document. The 620-megawatt plant, powered by a Westinghouse-pressurized water reactor, was completed three years ago. In its early stages, the project was shaken by allegations of kickbacks to officials of the <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> regime and by safety concerns. Communist rebels have bombed transmission towers leading from the plant, and people have cut and sold the copper lines as scrap. The plant's corps of operators has largely disbanded, and <ORGANIZATION> Westinghouse </ORGANIZATION> has only a handful of employees still in the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Woodson </PERSON> said. Yet the cost of the plant continues rising, <ORGANIZATION> Westinghouse </ORGANIZATION> said. Interest on the loans the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> took to build cost an estimated $ 300,000 per day.
