<HEAD>Wright Urges Bush To Move Quickly Against Budget Deficit</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: ADDS 3 final grafs with Bowen letter to OMB on health spending
cut proposals</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 House Speaker <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> on Wednesday called for <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> to quickly present <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> with an `` honest and responsible'' budget, saying the president-elect has a duty to spell out in detail his plan for attacking the country's deficit problems. <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> joined a chorus of witnesses before the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> who urged quick and decisive action on the part of the new administration and <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to break the seven-year deadlock over huge budget deficits. Former <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Volcker </PERSON>, who also testified, said that failure to act could trigger a loss of confidence by foreigners in the value of the dollar, sparking higher interest rates and possibly a severe recession in this country. `` We are, entirely unnecessarily in my view, undercutting the economic foundation of <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> world leadership,'' <PERSON> Volcker </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> said <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> should submit his own spending blueprint no later than mid-February and this should be followed by the recommendations of the economic commission by March 1. `` We do not have the luxury of a leisurely schedule,'' <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> said. `` The problems wo n't wait indefinitely while people try to read our lips or read our minds.'' <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> and other Democrats want to force <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> to be specific on how he would cut the deficit without raising taxes while still keeping his other campaign promises to boost spending in such areas as education, day care and environmental cleanup. They fear that unless the president-elect is forced to spell out how his spending cuts would work, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> will try later to blame <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> for boosting taxes while ignoring his `` flexible freeze'' approach. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said last week he intends to appoint people to begin deficit negotiations with <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> on his first day in office, but he has not said whether he will submit his own spending plan or simply use President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s final budget as the starting point for discussions. <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> said if <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> did not want to submit a separate budget then <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> should consider allowing <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> to incorporate his own recommendations into the administration's 1990 budget, which <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> will submit on Jan. 9. `` This would be an act of smooth transition and the kind of resolute leadership which could inspire greater confidence both from the public and from financial markets at home and abroad,'' <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Volcker </PERSON>, in his testimony, sounded many of the same warnings as his successor at the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Greenspan </PERSON>. In testimomy before the commission two weeks ago, <PERSON> Greenspan </PERSON> said the deficit had begun to `` eat away at the foundations of our economic strength, and the need to deal with it is becoming ever more urgent.'' <PERSON> Volcker </PERSON> said since the current economic recovery began in late 1982 the country has been on a consumption binge, fueled by the huge budget deficits and large flows of foreign capital into the country. To keep foreigners from losing confidence in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> economy, <PERSON> Volcker </PERSON> said the government needed to launch a credible deficit reduction program that would bring the deficit down by between $ 30 billion to $ 40 billion each year until the budget reaches surplus. The deficit in the last fiscal year was $ 155.1 billion. <PERSON> Volcker </PERSON> said he would favor using a gasoline tax to raise extra revenues, saying each 1-cent-per-gallon boost in the tax raises $ 1 billion annually in new revenues. This tax would promote conservation, <PERSON> Volcker </PERSON> said, thus reducing <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dependence on foreign oil and helping to trim <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s huge trade deficits. The Council on Competitiveness, composed of 157 chief executives from business, organized labor and higher education, presented the commission with a list of proposals to trim the deficit by $ 120 billion by 1993 with a combination of spending cuts and $ 48 billion in higher taxes. Among the taxes the council suggested were a boost in excise taxes on cigarettes and alcohol, which would raise $ 8 billion annually; a 20-cent-per-gallon increase in the gasoline tax, which would raise $ 20 billion annually; and higher income tax rates for families earning more than $ 220,350 a year, which could bring in $ 7 billion in additional revenues, the council said. Former Rep. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Giaimo </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Conn </LOCATION>., and co-chairman of the Committee for a <ORGANIZATION> Responsible </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION>, said a nationwide series of town meetings had shown him that Americans support balancing the budget, even it means tax increases and a freeze in cost-of-living hikes for Social Security <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Bowsher </PERSON>, head of the <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Accounting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION>, presented the commission with a <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> transition report which came to the conclusion that <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s flexible freeze would not be enough to eliminate the deficit and consideration would have to be given to increasing taxes. `` When the long-term health of our nation's economy is at stake, everything must be negotiable, including defense spending, entitlements and taxes,'' <PERSON> Bowsher </PERSON> said. Meanwhile, <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Otis </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bowen </PERSON> has registered his objections to proposals by the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION> to cut Medicaid payments to states next year and to reduce the growth in spending on AIDS. In a letter <PERSON> Bowen </PERSON> wrote to <ORGANIZATION> OMB </ORGANIZATION> Director <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, reported in Thursday's editions of <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION>, the secretary called the <ORGANIZATION> Medicaid </ORGANIZATION> proposal `` unrealistic.'' <ORGANIZATION> OMB </ORGANIZATION> wants to slash federal Medicaid payments to states by $ 1.1 billion, and to allow AIDS spending to grow from $ 1.3 billion to $ 1.6 billion. <PERSON> Bowen </PERSON> wants the government to spend $ 1.9 billion on AIDS.
