<SECOND>AM-Nerve Gas,0464</SECOND>
<HEAD>Authorities Investigating Alleged Scheme To Ship Nerve Gas To Iran</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Federal authorities are investigating an alleged scheme to illegally ship a chemical used to make nerve gas to <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Louis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post-Dispatch </ORGANIZATION> reported. Documents filed in <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Louis </LOCATION> say a company in <LOCATION> Baltimore </LOCATION> attempted to ship thiodiglycol, a chemical precursor of mustard gas, to <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> via <LOCATION> Singapore </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>, the <PERSON> Post-Dispatch </PERSON> said in its Thursday editions. The documents were filed in an application for a search warrant which sought telexes, computer printouts and records of messages between <ORGANIZATION> Alcolac </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Baltimore </LOCATION>, maker of the chemical, and two companies in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Singapore </LOCATION>. In the 8-year war between <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>, both sides _ but particularly <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> _ were accused of using chemical weapons. Both sides denied using the weapons, which are outlawed under the Geneva Convention. Thiodiglycol has permissible applications in the textile industry, but its export is restricted under <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> export laws `` to prevent diversion to <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION> for use in chemical warfare,'' the affidavit says. The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Customs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> outlined the scheme in a 14-page affidavit file in their application for the search warrant. The affidavit says <ORGANIZATION> Alcolac </ORGANIZATION> began shipping thiodiglycol in February 1987 for <ORGANIZATION> Colimex </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> GmbH </ORGANIZATION>, a West German company now called <ORGANIZATION> Chemco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> GmbH </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Co.. KG <ORGANIZATION> Alcolac </ORGANIZATION>'s shipping documents referred to the cargo by its trade name, <PERSON> Kromfax </PERSON>, rather by its chemical name. The documents had been manipulated to make it possible to divert the cargo to <LOCATION> Karachi </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>, in violation of <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Export Administration Regulations, the affidavit says. The cargo began its journey by barge from <LOCATION> Baltimore </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Norfolk </LOCATION>, where customs agents intercepted it and switched the Kromfax drums with drums of water. Customs agents then monitored the cargo's route to <LOCATION> Singapore </LOCATION> and its transshipment to <LOCATION> Karachi </LOCATION>. In late June, agents with the <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Enforcement </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> learned from customs officials in <LOCATION> Karachi </LOCATION> that the shipment had been transferred to an Iranian flagship named `` SS <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> Ekram.'' The cargo then made its way to the Iranian port at <PERSON> Bandar </PERSON> <PERSON> Abbas </PERSON>. It was set to be delivered ultimately to a company in <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION>, the capital of <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>. The affidavit says an undated telex from <LOCATION> Walaschek </LOCATION> to <ORGANIZATION> Alcolac </ORGANIZATION> indicates `` that he intended to cause the shipment of thiodiglycol to be transshipped from <LOCATION> Singapore </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>, and ultimately <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>, and that <ORGANIZATION> Alcolac </ORGANIZATION> knew that <LOCATION> Singapore </LOCATION> was not the ultimate destination for the shipment.'' <ORGANIZATION> Alcolac </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> was incorporated in <LOCATION> Baltimore </LOCATION> in 1955. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON>, vice president and general manager of the performance chemicals division, said the company manufactured `` specialty chemicals'' like those in shampoos. Thiodiglycol is a solvent, he said.
