<FIRST>r w PM-QuayleInterview Bjt   12-01 0741</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Quayle Interview, Bjt,730</SECOND>
<HEAD>Quayle May Preside More In Senate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN PUTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Vice President-elect <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> may spend more time than his predecessors presiding over the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, a move that could spell conflict between the Democratic-controlled chamber and the administration. In an interview, <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> on Wednesday also made his strongest public rejection of the notion that he will act as the link between the administration and the <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>'s far right. He also said his verbal gaffes during the campaign gave him some hard lessons about his own tendency to talk too much. Being besieged with questions and jokes about his qualifications was painful but educational, he said. `` I know myself better now. I'm a stronger person,'' he said. <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> said his focus now is on the task ahead _ picking his vice presidential staff during the transition period and working with President-elect <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>. Since the election, conservatives have beaten a path to <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>'s transition office seeking his ear <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> himself is an ardent conservative who has largely supported <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration positions during his eight years in the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>. `` I've worked with a number of conservatives in the past; a lot of good friends are conservatives, but I'm not the point man for the conservatives in this administration. ... You wo n't see me being the so-called spear carrier for all the so-called conservative issues,'' <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> also hinted that he may take a more active role in his official capacity as president of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, presiding over the Democratic-controlled chamber more frequently. `` It's certainly an option. ... There have been suggestions to me by many that I consider spending more time in the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> than my predecessors have. I have not made a decision on that,'' he said. The presiding officer has substantial discretion as to which senator to recognize for the purpose of offering amendments, bills and motions. Normally the chair is occupied by a member of the majority party. A Republican in charge could touch off partisan parliamentary warfare. The vice president may take the presiding chair at any time, and the presiding officer's decision to recognize a senator is not subject to a point of order or appeal under <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> rules. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has said he wants to work with <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, and <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> said if he did decide to preside more often, it would not be done `` in a contentious manner.'' `` I would be fair and objective and do what the president of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> should do to protect senators' rights, all senators' rights,'' he said During the interview, <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> was relaxed and friendly, but clearly weighing his words. He has not generally spoken to the press in depth since the election. He confessed to being `` far more careful of what I say today than six months ago.'' `` I also try to discipline myself when I get into a situation ... instead of being verbose, which is a tendency that I have, to be concise. Because verbosity leads to unclear, inarticulate things.'' Also on Wednesday, <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> met with retiring <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Orr </PERSON>, a Republican who will appoint <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>'s replacement in the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> will resign effective Jan. 2 so his replacement can have seniority over other incoming senators. <PERSON> Orr </PERSON> has not said whom he will appoint, and <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> said he made no recommendation. But he did not reject a reporter's suggestion that he favors Rep. <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Coats </PERSON>, who was <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>'s district representative in <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Wayne </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ind. </LOCATION>, while <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> was in the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> from 1976 to 1980. Coats now represents <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>'s old congressional district. `` Obviously I think a lot of <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Coats </PERSON>. He worked for me for four years. He's been a very good congressman from my old congressional district. He took my seat. We've had a long and strong personal and professional relationship,'' <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> said. On another subject, <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> said the vice presidential mansion in the <LOCATION> District </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION> may need alterations before his family can move in after the inauguration. He said the house is not configured for a family with three children. It does have six bedrooms, but some of them now serve as offices and servants' quarters and some do not have closets. The Quayles will live at their home in <LOCATION> McLean </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, until they can move into the official residence. Their three children _ <PERSON> Tucker </PERSON>, 14, <PERSON> Benjamin </PERSON>, 12, and <PERSON> Corinne </PERSON>, 10 _ will continue attending public schools in <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> for the time being.
