<HEAD>Bentsen, Pickle Say Funding Atom Smasher Will Be Tough</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER DIXON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Texans in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> will have a tough time persuading their colleagues to spend the billions of dollars needed to build the super collider, Sen. <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> says. `` I'll be working very hard to get it funded,'' <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> said. `` It's going to be exceedingly difficult to get.'' Even when seven states were candidates for the potentially lucrative physics project, <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> was adamant about financing the super collider. It voted earlier this year to give the project $ 100 million _ less than one-third of President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s request for $ 363 million _ and decreed none of the money could be spent on construction. `` It's going to be uphill and tough, and particularly now because it's just one state,'' <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON>, chairman of the influential <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, told a group of <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> reporters in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> on Wednesday. `` We had seven states working on it before.'' Now that a site in <LOCATION> Ellis </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> has been chosen by the <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> for the super collider, at least one member of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> from a state that lost its bid to host the project is questioning the feasibility of finding enough construction money. The super collider is expected to cost $ 4.4 billion, and to create thousands of construction and scientific jobs. Rep. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Dingell </PERSON>, D-Mich., said last week that the superconducting super collider was in trouble and would likely be doomed by budget constraints and opposition from others in the scientific community `` And quite honestly, the way the program has been set up, the consequences are that there's really very limited support outside of one particular state,'' said <PERSON> Dingell </PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. `` I have n't said it's going to go down the drain, but it's in serious difficulty.'' He said it stood a chance of one or two in 10 of ever being built.
