<SECOND>PM-AIDS Day-US,370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Letters From Victims Mark AIDS Day Observance</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY ESTILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A 20-year-old <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION> resident wrote a top federal health official that the public reaction to disclosing he tested positive for the AIDS virus would end his life `` sooner than AIDS will probably take it.'' The letter from `` D'' _ his identity is known to <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> officials _ was among eight from people with AIDS being read today during a World AIDS Day ceremony at the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION>. `` I live in the Bible Belt of our country,'' began the letter to Dr. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Windom </PERSON>, the No. 2 physician in the federal health department. `` I have lived most of my life in a small town in <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION>. I attend a large university in <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION> and will soon be finishing my junior year. `` I ca n't tell you my name because my short life of only 20 years would be over very quickly. It would be over sooner than AIDS will probably take it. I'm HIV positive and have been so diagnosed since spring of 1987. `` I sit in classrooms and hear people discuss AIDS and what they think they know is right. Why ca n't I speak up and tell them they ca n't get it from just being in the same room? Why ca n't I tell them the truth? `` I'm so afraid of what will happen if I openly admit to being HIV positive. Would I get kicked out of school? I was so afraid of what people would think, I did n't even talk to my parents about it for six months. I was hurting so bad. I was lonely. `` Now, my father has never even said the word AIDS and my mother only makes sure I'm in good health and eating right and taking vitamins.'' <PERSON> Windom </PERSON>, the assistant secretary for health, arranged the program, including an opening minute of silence for the people who have died of AIDS. As of Nov. 7, 1988, AIDS had been diagnosed in 77,994 Americans, of whom more than half, or 43,888, have died since June 1, 1981, according to the <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION>. No one is known to have recovered from AIDS.
