<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Tower </PERSON>, the former senator and leading candidate to be Secretary of <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> in the next administration, is registered as a lobbyist for five large defense companies, according to a Tower associate and congressional records. Tower, former chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Armed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, is the chief candidate to take over the top Pentagon spot, but President-elect <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has n't yet made a final decision, according to sources speaking Wednesday on condition of anonymity. Some <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> aides oppose Tower because they fear he would n't push hard enough to reform the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION>'s problem-plagued system for buying weapons, the sources said. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> sidestepped the question Wednesday. Asked by reporters about reports of staff dissension over Tower, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said only, `` stay tuned,'' repeating his favorite refrain on administration nominations. He said `` all is tranquil'' within his staff. Representatives of <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and Tower are negotiating over who might be named to high-level <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> jobs, the sources said. Tower, 63, retired from <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> in 1985 after a 24-year career in the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, capped by his chairmanship of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Armed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> during President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s first term. After he retired, Tower was named by <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> as a member of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> team negotiating with the Soviets for deep cuts in the U.S.-Soviet arsenals of long-range weapons. He quit after 14 months in that post and set up a consulting firm, <ORGANIZATION> Tower </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associates </ORGANIZATION>. Early this year, the White House asked Tower to help lobby his former <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> colleagues to ratify the treaty ridding <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> of medium-range nuclear weapons, said <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Billmire </PERSON>, a Tower associate. Tower did not return telephone calls. But <PERSON> Billmire </PERSON> said the company registered Feb. 2 as a lobbyist because Tower did n't want any conflict-of-interest questions raised about his work on the Intermediate-range Nuclear Forces treaty, as the agreement is known. <ORGANIZATION> Tower </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associates </ORGANIZATION> is registered as a lobbyist for <ORGANIZATION> Martin-Marietta </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Textron </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> LTV </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aerospace </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aerospace </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Rockwell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION>. Tower is a consultant to the five firms, <PERSON> Billmire </PERSON> said, and as such would not be required to register as a lobbyist unless he lobbied <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> on their behalf. `` We registered because the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> asked for our help on the INF treaty and we were working as consultants for these companies at the same time,'' said <PERSON> Billmire </PERSON>. `` The companies make some components which go into systems that are used for weapons affected by the treaty,'' he explained. `` Tower wanted to be absolutely clear and up front about his connections with the companies and he did n't want anybody saying that the reason Tower was saying this or that about the treaty was because it would have helped one of his clients.'' <PERSON> Billmire </PERSON> declined to say what the firm was paid by the five companies. But Tower might be expected to have received more than $ 50,000 annually from each, according to a defense contractor who spoke Wednesday on condition he not be named. Tower is also a member of the board of directors of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> subsidiary of British Aerospace. That subsidiary is based in <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION>.
