<HEAD>Agreement Reached On New Contract for Guild-Covered Staff at AP</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Associated Press and the <ORGANIZATION> Wire </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guild </ORGANIZATION> agreed on a new collective bargaining agreement covering 1,400 employees, including the news service's domestic reporting and editing staff. The two-year accord came minutes before midnight Wednesday, when the preceding pact was to expire. The Guild's negotiating committee voted to recommend the agreement for approval by its membership. The new contract provides the <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION> news staff with a top-minimum salary of $ 720 per week, after increases of $ 27 a week in the first year and $ 25 a week in the second year. In addition, the agreement provided significant increases for <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION>'s non-news personnel. Among fringe benefit improvements, the contract provides for extension of dental health coverage to cover part of the cost of orthodontic treatment, and a doubling of the eye-care reimbursement benefit to $ 100 annually. New benefits were creation of a non-matching 401K retirement savings plan and establishment of an account to provide tax deferred benefits to staffers making arrangements for child care or other dependent care. <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION> also established a 100 percent reimbursement for certain preventive cancer screening tests. Aside from the general increase, the agreement also provides for improvements in the economic differential received by <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION> news staffers in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>. Staffers in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> received increases of $ 10 in the first year and $ 12 in the second year, providing a total differential of $ 87. In <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>, the increase was $ 5 in the first year and $ 7 in the second year, providing a total differential of $ 45. The contract agreement also resolved a unit clarification petition filed by the <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION> and a companion petition filed by the Guild. The petitions asked the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Relations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> to clarify the supervisory status of <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> editors and correspondents, a subject that had been considered but not definitively resolved by the <ORGANIZATION> NLRB </ORGANIZATION> in 1982. The Guild and the <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION> agreed that all news editors and correspondents supervising three or more employes would be exempt from Guild jurisdiction and thus become members of AP management. Correspondents who supervise smaller <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION> operations would remain in <LOCATION> Guild </LOCATION> jurisdiction, the parties agreed. <ORGANIZATION> NLRB </ORGANIZATION> hearings, set to begin in December, will be canceled as a result of the agreement, in which the <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION> said news editors or correspondents who wished to maintain their place in the Guild bargaining unit could relinquish their supervisory duties and transfer to regular staff positions. The parties also resolved several significant pension issues, striking a mandatory contribution clause that required the AP to contribute $ 2,881 per week to a pension trust that was already fully funded. The parties further agreed that funds held in the AP account in The Newspaper Guild Commingled Fund could be used for payments of pension benefits and expenses, retroactive through 1988. Bargaining on the contract began in October. The guild was represented by AP news staffers from around the nation who are members of the union.
</TEXT>
