<HEAD>Vietnam Frees Archbishop After 13 Years Imprisonment</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VATICAN CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Vietnamese government has released a Roman Catholic archbishop after 13 years in prison without trial, the <ORGANIZATION> Vatican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION> said. The radio said Wednesday that Archbishop <PERSON> Francesco </PERSON> <PERSON> Saverio </PERSON> <PERSON> Nguyen </PERSON> <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Thuan </PERSON>, 60, was released by police around mid-November. <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Thuan </PERSON> was promoted to the position of archbishop-coadjutor in <LOCATION> Ho </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Chi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Minh </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> in April of 1975 and was arrested several months later, the report said. In the early 1970s, <PERSON> Nguyen </PERSON> <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Thuan </PERSON> was assigned by the Vietnamese bishop's conference to help victims of the Vietnam War and was considered `` anti-revolutionary'' by the communist authorities, the report said. The report said that during the 13 years, <PERSON> Nguyen </PERSON> <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Thuan </PERSON> was held in prison, re-education camps, and under house arrest. The news of <PERSON> Nguyen </PERSON> <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Thuan </PERSON>'s release reached the <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> through Cardinal <PERSON> Trinh </PERSON> <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Can </PERSON>, archbishop of <LOCATION> Hanoi </LOCATION>, the report said.
