<FIRST>r a PM-Alzheimer'sTown Bjt   12-01 0644</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Alzheimer's Town, Bjt,0661</SECOND>
<HEAD>Town Holds Daylong Seminar on Alzheimer's</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DIAMOND</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WESTPORT, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Third-grader <PERSON> Victoria </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> told her classmates in a hushed voice how her grandmother looked at wedding pictures and could not remember the names of her own family members. <PERSON> Matthew </PERSON> <PERSON> Ouelette </PERSON>, another <ORGANIZATION> Westport </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Elementary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> pupil, recalled how his neighbor, an elderly woman, `` forgot how to drive,'' and `` forgot how to cook.'' Like practically everyone in their coastal town of 1,850 residents, the pupils were talking about Alzheimer's disease as part of a day-long series of events Wednesday put together by educators, doctors and a drug company. `` This is a test to see how much you can educate an entire town in one day,'' said <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Connolly </PERSON> of New Jersey-based <ORGANIZATION> Sandoz </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pharmaceuticals </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp </ORGANIZATION>. The program used coloring books, a mascot dog and movies to show how the debilitating ailment can be battled. For a few hours, the students put aside their reading, writing and arithmetic to look at a disease that may not afflict them for 60 years, if at all. The children wanted to know how Alzheimer's disease gets started and, as it happens, that was one question that could not be answered definitively. The purpose of the effort was not so much to understand how the disease works but to show how the loved ones of an Alzheimer's sufferer can, with patience, helpful advice and love, minimize the worst of the disease's effects <LOCATION> Westport </LOCATION>, which is in the third year of a federal <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> grant intended to promote community programs, developed the Alzheimer's effort in meetings between school officials and <PERSON> Connolly </PERSON>, who spends summers here. <ORGANIZATION> Sandoz </ORGANIZATION> manufactures Hydergine, a drug that can ease some symptoms of Alzheimer's in milder cases. For adults, Wednesday's program included discussions on `` positive approaches to aging,'' a film titled `` There Were Times Dear,'' dramatizing a family coping with Alzheimer's, and a lecture by Dr. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Gershell </PERSON>, a specialist in geriatrics at <ORGANIZATION> Mount </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sinai </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>. Alzheimer's afflicts an estimated 5 million mostly elderly Americans. Efforts are expanding to help them cope. Until recently, the focus was on patients, not their families. <LOCATION> Westport </LOCATION> is changing that emphasis because of mounting evidence that children are often acutely aware of and confused by the decline of a loved one. A coloring book titled `` Helping Grandma,'' by <ORGANIZATION> Westport </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> High </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> art teacher <PERSON> Betsey </PERSON> <PERSON> MacDonald </PERSON>, told the story of a grandmother who gradually begins to show signs of memory loss. `` Children are often kept in the dark about aging,'' said <PERSON> MacDonald </PERSON>. `` They automatically think that ` old' means ` sick.' But children are wonderfully resilient and surprisingly insightful when spoken to directly on the subject.'' The point of the coloring book, geared toward elementary school children, is to `` teach them understanding and to teach them that what she needs is support.'' <PERSON> Connolly </PERSON> said a key problem with the disease is the failure to recognize that it is a problem. `` The feeling is that to be old is to be sick and to be old is to be confused,'' <PERSON> Connolly </PERSON> said. Children ask what is wrong with an elderly relative and `` parents say, ` Well, <PERSON> Grandma </PERSON>'s getting old.' That's not true.'' One of the first things relatives can do for those showing signs of memory loss or other dementia is encourage them to go to a doctor. Also, mature, well-behaved dogs from an animal shelter can provide some stability and love for an Alzheimer's sufferer, <PERSON> Connolly </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Jeff </PERSON>, a black and white mongrel from a <LOCATION> Rhode </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> animal shelter, has become the national poster dog for the so-called human-animal bonding campaign, and he travels with <PERSON> Connolly </PERSON> to events on the subject. The Alzheimer's event in this southern <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> community was the second of its kind. <PERSON> Connolly </PERSON>, <PERSON> MacDonald </PERSON> and <PERSON> Jeff </PERSON> tried out the program earlier this fall in <LOCATION> Bloomington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ind </LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
