<HEAD>Researcher Recommends Hats and Sunglasses To Prevent Cataracts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL Q. HANEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 People who wear hats and sunglasses to protect their eyes from strong sunshine could substantially reduce the risk of cataracts, says the author of a study published today. The research, conducted on fishermen, found that frequent exposure to intense sun tripled the risk of a common form of cataracts, strengthening the widely held suspicion that too much sun is bad for the eyes, just as it is for the skin. `` If there is enough sunshine for you to get sunburned, then you should be protecting your eyes,'' said Dr. <PERSON> Hugh </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Johns </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hopkins </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. He noted that many people have gotten used to smearing sunblock on their faces to prevent skin cancer. But they leave their eyes exposed to damaging ultraviolet light, the invisible portion of the sunbeam that burns the skin and slowly clouds the lens of the eyes. <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON> said the easiest way to protect the eyes is to put on a hat with a brim. `` That will cut UV exposure to the eye by 50 percent. And if you get sunglasses, you can eliminate all ocular UV exposure or cut it down by 80 percent to 90 percent,'' he said in an interview. Cataracts are a common health problem, resulting in more than 1 million operations in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> each year. <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON> and colleagues estimated the annual ultraviolet exposures of 838 <LOCATION> Chesapeake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION> watermen, who work on boats. These varied, depending on how much they fished, the time of year they were on the water and whether they wore hats and glasses, among other factors. Doctors found no association between sunlight and cataracts of the nucleus of the lens. However, they found that it was strongly associated with cataracts of the surrounding cortex of the lens. Cortical and nuclear cataracts each account for about one-third of all cases that require surgery. Not enough fishermen in the study had a third variety of eye damage, known as posterior subcapsular cataracts, to determine whether they also are caused by sunlight. The study, published in the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> England </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Journal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medicine </ORGANIZATION>, found that the higher the men's exposure to ultraviolet light, the greater their risk of cortical cataracts. The researchers divided the watermen into four groups, depending on the intensity of their exposure. The quarter with the highest annual exposure had three times the risk of those in the group with the lowest exposure. The research showed that people who got cortical cataracts received, on average, 21 percent more ultraviolet light than those who did not. Doubling the annual ultraviolet exposure increased the cataract risk by 60 percent. In an accompanying editorial, Dr. <PERSON> Sidney </PERSON> <PERSON> Lerman </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> wrote that prevention of light damage to the eye `` is the best and simplest approach to the problem.'' <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON> said that all glasses, including ordinary reading glasses, cut exposure significantly, although they vary in effectiveness. The best are plastic lenses specifically designed to block ultraviolet rays. These can stop virtually all of these rays from reaching the eyes. He said that ordinary, untinted glass spectacles stop about 80 percent of ultraviolet radiation, while similar plastic lenses keep out 90 percent. Run-of-the-mill cheap sunglasses block about 95 percent.
</TEXT>
