<HEAD>Dismissed Dental Student Files Suit over AIDS Exposure</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A student who was dismissed from the <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> dental school for treating patients after testing positive for exposure to the AIDS virus has sued the school for $ 3 million in damages. The student, whose name is listed in the suit as <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Doe </PERSON>, claims the school improperly barred him from its dental program last summer. Attorney <PERSON> Norman </PERSON> <PERSON> London </PERSON> contends his client is handicapped and can not be discriminated against. The suit, filed Wednesday in <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Louis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>, also names <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> chancellor <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Danforth </PERSON> and <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bensinger </PERSON>, dean of the dental school. The suit does not seek to have the student reinstated, but asks for $ 3 million in damages, contending the use of rubber gloves and other protective devices makes the risk of transmitting the virus negligible. School officials said the student treated 27 patients at the dental school for about a year after contracting the disease. <PERSON> Bensinger </PERSON> said the student tested positive for antibodies to the human immunodefiency syndrome _ HIV _ in late March or early April. The student was dismissed from the school in August and was not allowed to enroll for the current school year. Students and instructional faculty members provide dental care at the school's clinic. University officials refused to comment on the suit. <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Ruger </PERSON>, the university's general counsel, said that the dental school was well within its rights in barring the student from treating patients and pursuing his education.
