<FIRST>u i PM-Soviet-Government 1stLd-Writethru   12-01 0750</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Government, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0464,0771</SECOND>
<HEAD>Political Reforms Alone Won't Make Soviet Union Democratic</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: SUBS 3rd graf, `The 1,500...' to UPDATE with parliamentary
vote. Pickup 4th, `Gorbachev's promise...</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Soviet President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> says constitutional and electoral reforms are `` a kind of oxygen'' to revive the body politic, but it is unlikely they alone can make his society any more democratic. Since the proposed reforms appeared on Oct. 22-23, Soviet society has been engaged in a remarkable debate over an overhaul of the electoral system and the structure of the government that <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> says is the first big step toward making Soviet society into one governed by law rather than dictate. The 1,500 members of the Supreme Soviet parliament today overwhelmingly approved the package, the amended version of which still has not been published in the official press. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s promise is a weighty one in a society now reopening the emotional and physical scars of <PERSON> Josef </PERSON> <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON>'s purges and still suffering from a much more recent history of systematic jailing or exile of dissidents and overbearing bureaucracy. But political reforms do not guarantee change. Political repression has been imposed in a Soviet system that on paper guaranteed citizens' rights. The <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> has shown no interest in sharing power. And operating in the current system, critics have used <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s policy of `` glasnost,'' or greater openness, to force some changes in his proposals. `` Political reform is a kind of oxygen needed by the public organism,'' <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> told the Supreme Soviet on Tuesday, the first day of a special session to consider the reform package. `` If we do not carry out political reform to back up the processes that are now under way in the economy, the social transformation of society and the recuperation in the cultural field, and fail to radically update the activities of the governing councils and our personnel, the drive for restructuring will inevitably begin to skid,'' he said. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> said his solution is `` our own socialist system of ` checks and balances' ... designed to protect society against any violations of socialist legality at the highest state level.'' He called for the formation of a <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Deputies </ORGANIZATION>, a new 2,250-member legislative body formed not only in elections from geographic districts and ethnic territories, but from organizations such as the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> and trade unions. Draft legislation gave the presidency, which <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> assumed Oct. 1, considerably more power, and appeared as well to strengthen <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>'s hand with the 15 republics that make up the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. The proposals loosened an avalanche of more than 300,000 suggestions from across the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, and protests from at least a third of the republics that some of the reforms fostered the opposite of <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s proclaimed intention to give local authorities more power. In the spirit of `` glasnost,'' Soviet leaders got an earful of criticism that led them to amend about half of the almost 120 articles before introducing them to the Supreme Soviet on Monday. In two days of rare debate, deputies of the Supreme Soviet offered many more. `` The discussion itself, I'll tell you frankly, is unprecedented,'' Soviet Vice President <PERSON> Anatoly </PERSON> <PERSON> Lukyanov </PERSON> told a news conference. The tiny Baltic republic of <LOCATION> Estonia </LOCATION>, where <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s policy of greater openness already encouraged a grassroots political movement to demand greater autonomy, has declared itself `` sovereign'' in internal affairs and proclaiming the right to pass judgment on new Soviet laws. Similar organizations in the other Baltic republics of <LOCATION> Latvia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Lithuania </LOCATION> were close behind but could not push the legislation through their parliaments. The Presidium of the national Supreme Soviet declared <LOCATION> Estonia </LOCATION>'s action unconstitutional <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> also must rein in the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> and government bureaucracies that are stubbornly resistant to change. The president told the Supreme Soviet that many initiatives from working people `` are being lost in bureaucratic mazes, or are even encountering resistance.'' He won approval at the June party conference for a plan to get the party out of day-to-day management of government and economic affairs, concentrating instead on setting policy. He has called for taking power from the <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> and giving it to local economic managers along with the responsibility of ensuring they make enough money to pay for their operations. But the Soviet leader regularly expresses frustration with both the party and government bureaucracy's slow pace of change.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Porubcansky </PERSON> is a correspondent in the <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> bureau of <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>.
