<HEAD>Justice Training Council Approves Police Cadet Training Reforms</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANA KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEEDHAM, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The state council on police training approved reforms, including minimum physical fitness standards for cadets and certification for instructors, in the wake of a 25-year-old cadet's death. The <ORGANIZATION> Criminal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Training </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> voted overwhelmingly for the new measures in this <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> suburb Wednesday as a coroner's inquest into the death of Cadet <PERSON> Timothy </PERSON> <PERSON> Shepard </PERSON> continued in <LOCATION> Springfield </LOCATION> The council reiterated its abolition of `` modified stress training,'' which combined constant exercise with unexpected situations and conflicting orders. Such methods were partly blamed for the dehydration suffered by cadets at the <LOCATION> Agawam </LOCATION> training academy near <LOCATION> Springfield </LOCATION> in September. <PERSON> Shepard </PERSON> collapsed on the first day of training Sept. 19 at the academy after a day of rigorous training with few breaks for water. He died six weeks later of complications from heat stroke, a coroner has ruled. Fifteen other cadets were hospitalized the first week of training. The measures approved Wednesday are part of a 120-day `` action plan'' which will go into effect with the start of new training classes in January, according to <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Agnes </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, the council's interim executive director The plan is intended to become part of a permanent, comprehensive program for teaching police recruits. `` We will have made a clean break with the past,'' <PERSON> Agnes </PERSON> told council members and a panel that included Attorney General <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Shannon </PERSON>. `` We will set the agenda for the future by laying the groundwork now.'' Among other rules adopted Wednesday: _ Injuries to student officers must be documented and recorded; _ Physical or academic punishment to teach, enforce or maintain discipline is prohibited; _ Establishment of a new discipline policy, including a merit-demerit system; _ Pre-admission drug screening and physicals by qualified physicians; _ More rigorous rules for academic performance, including standardization of all written tests; _ Creation of new qualifications and certification for all academy directors and instructors; _ All academy directors and instructors must read the attorney general's report of what happened during training this year; _ Pre-admission orientation on physical and academic aspects of police training. The council also accepted the resignation of Assistant Director <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Canty </PERSON> and authorized the dismissals of <PERSON> Judith </PERSON> <PERSON> Crossen </PERSON>, director of training; <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Michaelman </PERSON>, pre-screening coordinator and <PERSON> Earl </PERSON> <PERSON> Harrington </PERSON>, former zone manager for western <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Brian </PERSON> <PERSON> Daley </PERSON>, director of standards, will be reassigned to new duties, the council said.
