<HEAD>House Makes History By Electing Co-speakers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUG RICHARDSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Co-speakers, co-chairmen, cooperation. That's the plan for the restructured <ORGANIZATION> Indiana </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, its leaders say The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, split 50-50 between Democrats and Republicans, elected co-speakers for the first time Wednesday and adopted a special agreement that redistributes many of the speaker's powers to the chamber's members. Democrat <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> K. </PERSON> <PERSON> Phillips </PERSON> and Republican <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Mannweiler </PERSON> were named co-speakers by unanimous voice votes in the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, which went from a 52-48 <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> majority to an even split after the Democrats picked up two seats in the Nov. 8 election. The two men, who negotiated the power-sharing agreement over 2 -LCB- days last week, jointly clutched the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> gavel and raised it aloft as the membership stood cheering and applauding. `` This is a historic occasion, one in which we all can take a great deal of pride,'' said <PERSON> Mannweiler </PERSON>, who presided alone as <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> speaker the last two years. The two men will preside over the chamber on alternate days. <PERSON> Phillips </PERSON> went first, wielding the gavel after the speaker election. <PERSON> Mannweiler </PERSON> will get his turn when the House reconvenes Jan. 4. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> minority leader for the last 12 years, <PERSON> Phillips </PERSON> quoted poet <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Frost </PERSON> in a speech urging `` conciliation, not confrontation'' during the 1989 session. `` We're taking the road less traveled by, and that will make all the difference,'' he said. `` I'm convinced the system will work.'' The co-speaker arrangement and a series of rules changes were negotiated after the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> tried unsuccessfully last week to elect a speaker. Under the agreement, each committee will have <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> co-chairmen and equal membership from each party. The <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> speaker will appoint committee members from his party and assign Republican-authored bills to committee. The Democratic speaker will do the same for his party. If a co-chairman does not want to hold a hearing on a bill, his counterpart from the other party can draw on his allotment of `` wild cards'' to keep the bill moving. A tie vote in a committee will send a bill to the floor without recommendation. Previously, a bill died if it did not win a majority vote in committee. Once a bill reaches the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> floor, the author can control when it is called down for amendment and a final vote. Formerly, the speaker controlled the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> calendar of bills and exercised his greatest power by killing bills through refusing to call them for votes.
