Pickup 5th graf pvs, ``China, the...''</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Foreign Minister <PERSON> Qian </PERSON> <PERSON> Qichen </PERSON> of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> arrived today for the first foreign-ministry level talks between the two communist powers on Soviet soil in 31 years. `` <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, as two great neighboring countries, must live in peace and good-neighborly relations,'' <PERSON> Qian </PERSON> said in a statement distributed by the Soviet news agency <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION>. `` We are glad that in recent years Chinese-Soviet relations gradually are improving. I sincerely hope this visit will end with the expecte results.'' <PERSON> Qian </PERSON> was greeted at <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Sheremetyevo </ORGANIZATION> 2 airport by Foreign Minister <PERSON> Eduard </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON>, with whom he will conduct two days of talks that will include laying the groundwork for a <ORGANIZATION> Chinese-Soviet </ORGANIZATION> summit meeting next year. The Chinese foreign minister also said he expects to meet with President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>. Before leaving <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Qian </PERSON> said the focus of his talks will be the war in <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION>, the major stumbling block to restoring normal Chinese-Soviet ties. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, the main backer of anti-Vietnamese resistance forces in <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION>, insists that <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> exert pressure on its ally <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> to end its 10-year military occupation of that <LOCATION> Southeast </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Asian </LOCATION> country. The last Chinese foreign minister to visit <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> was <PERSON> Chou </PERSON> <PERSON> En-lai </PERSON> in 1957. No Soviet foreign minister has made an official visit to <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> since <PERSON> Andrei </PERSON> <PERSON> Gromyko </PERSON> accompanied then Soviet leader <PERSON> Nikita </PERSON> <PERSON> Khrushchev </PERSON> in 1959. In 1960, <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> split after <PERSON> Mao </PERSON> <PERSON> Tse-tung </PERSON> accused <PERSON> Khrushchev </PERSON> of `` revisionism'' and compromising with the capitalist West. The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> responded by withdrawing Soviet engineers and technology from hundreds of joint projects, dealing a painful blow to <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s fragile industrial base. Relations reached a low in 1969 when the two sides fought a short war along their disputed border. <PERSON> Mao </PERSON> called on the nation to prepare for all-out war, and each side stationed at least 1 million troops along the border. The countries began normalization talks in 1982, opening the way for a general easing of tensions and a gradual increase in trade, scientific and cultural exchanges. <PERSON> Qian </PERSON> noted that the two sides held vice foreign minister-level talks in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> last August on <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> and that he had discussed the issue with Soviet Foreign Minister <PERSON> Eduard </PERSON> <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON> in a meeting at the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> in September. Both sides, <PERSON> Qian </PERSON> said, `` have indicated their willingness to make an effort to bring about an early settlement to the Kampuchean -LRB- <LOCATION> Cambodian </LOCATION> -RRB- question on a just and reasonable basis, including the <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> troop withdrawal.'' <PERSON> Qian </PERSON> also indicated that the first Chinese-Soviet summit since <PERSON> Khrushchev </PERSON> met <PERSON> Mao </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> in 1959 was a certainty, regardless of further progress on <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION>. That summit is scheduled next year in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>. Asked if the summit was linked to solving the Cambodian question, <PERSON> Qian </PERSON> said, `` Now the conditions for the summit meeting in the view of both sides are getting ready and both sides are making preparations for his summit.'' He said his visit and a return visit to <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>, probably next month, by <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON> `` will all be part of the preparations.'' Chinese leaders have said a summit could take place in the first half of 1989. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> is expected to come to <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> because <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s senior leader <PERSON> Deng </PERSON> <PERSON> Xiaoping </PERSON>, 84, rarely travels abroad. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> has continued to insist `` three obstacles'' remain, headed by <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION>, that must be solved before full normalization can be realized. <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> has taken steps to remove the other two obstacles by pulling out of <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> and reducing tension along the border by withdrawing one army division facing <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> from Soviet ally <LOCATION> Mongolia </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Qian </PERSON> said he will discuss the estimated 50,000 Soviet troops still in <LOCATION> Mongolia </LOCATION>, `` which should be pulled out,'' border disputes and `` the Soviet military gathering along the Chinese-Soviet border.''
