 Christmas furloughs for a triple murderer and other inmates of a maximum security prison may be revoked because of public outcry, while police sought an escapee from the same prison in the rape of a 40-year-old woman. While the <ORGANIZATION> Patuxent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institution </ORGANIZATION> review board ponders the furloughs and may decide the matter today, a warrant has been issued for <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Stavarakas </PERSON>, the prime suspect in a rape of a 40-year-old woman in the <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>, suburb of <LOCATION> Hyattsville </LOCATION>. The attack bears a startling resemblance to the crime that landed Stavarakas in prison in 1979, authorities said. He escaped Monday from the prison in <LOCATION> Jessup </LOCATION>, about 20 miles southwest of <LOCATION> Baltimore </LOCATION>, where he was serving a 25-year sentence. The victim's general description of the attacker matched that of <LOCATION> Stavarakas </LOCATION>, and she noted distinctive tattoos, said <ORGANIZATION> Maryland </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Capital </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Park </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Police </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Davis </PERSON>. In addition, the rape occurred near the same park as Stavarakas' 1978 assault. Meanwhile, a <ORGANIZATION> Howard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> judge on Wednesday issued a temporary injunction blocking Patuxent officials from granting additional furloughs to triple murderer <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Angell </PERSON> for at least 10 days. The order was requested by the <ORGANIZATION> Montgomery </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Police </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, which has filed suit to force <PERSON> Angell </PERSON>'s transfer to another prison. <PERSON> Angell </PERSON>, 31, was sentenced to three life terms for the murders of two <LOCATION> Montgomery </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> police officers and a teen-ager. Judge <PERSON> Cornelius </PERSON> <PERSON> Sybert </PERSON> said the injunction would expire at midnight Dec. 9. A police association attorney said he would apply then for a 10-day extension of the order. Lt. <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>, a spokesman for the police association, said he was pleased with <PERSON> Sybert </PERSON>'s ruling. `` I do n't think we can afford the luxury of gambling on <PERSON> Angell </PERSON>,'' he said. `` He forfeited his right to freedom when he murdered three people.'' The association filed the suit after reports that <PERSON> Angell </PERSON> had been granted 11 furloughs to visit his family since April. The corrections department put an end to the visits in the ensuing furor and canceled <PERSON> Angell </PERSON>'s planned Thanksgiving leave. Patuxent is the only institution in the country which has independent powers to grant paroles and supervised furloughs, a power some state officials want to review because of the outcry caused by the <PERSON> Angell </PERSON> case.
