<SECOND>PM-World AIDS Day,0552</SECOND>
<HEAD>World AIDS Day Opens With Messages From Reagan, Pope, AIDS Victim</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENDA WATSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, Pope <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> II and one of the longest living AIDS victims sent messages to the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> today on the first World AIDS Day. The messages called for a stepped-up fight against AIDS and for compassion for its victims. The agency organized World AIDS Day to encourage governments and communities to talk about the disease, which affects an estimated 300,000 people worldwide. It said 140 countries planned special television and radio programs and dances, parades and song contests. Entertainer Pearl <PERSON> Bailey </PERSON> told officials at <ORGANIZATION> WHO </ORGANIZATION> headquarters that she knows a 29-year-old man with AIDS and that she wants to dedicate her life to the fight against the disease. Also present was <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Rector </PERSON>, a 32-year-old <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> man who has had AIDS for six years. <PERSON> Rector </PERSON> said World AIDS Day should be `` the opening paragraph in a new chapter of our worldwide effort to stop AIDS.'' <PERSON> Rector </PERSON>, currently based in <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION>, said he has traveled to three continents to teach people about AIDS. Officially, 142 countries have reported 129,385 cases of AIDS to the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION>. But the agency estimates that the true number is more than twice that, and that 5 to 10 million people may be infected with the virus that causes AIDS. Once a person is infected with the virus, he or she has a 50 percent chance of developing AIDS within 10 years. There is no known cure for AIDS, which attacks the body's immune system. The agency has emphasized education as a primary means to fight the spread of the infection, which can be transmitted through blood, sexual intercourse, and from an infected mother to her unborn or newborn child. People at high risk of infection include those with numerous sex partners and intravenous drug users who share needles. Dr. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Mason </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Centers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disease </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>, told the opening ceremony that the `` spread of infection in some high risk groups in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is clearly declining.'' He said this was because `` some infected and non-infected individuals practicing risky behavior have adopted safe or less risky lifestyles.'' <PERSON> Mason </PERSON> noted that the first cases of AIDS were recognized in 1981, in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, and that 78,985 Americans have gotten AIDS and 44,334 have died from it. But he also said: `` AIDS has stimulated an unprecedented scientific and medical research effort that will have long-term benefit in combating AIDS and other diseases as well.'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> called knowledge `` a critical weapon'' in fighting AIDS, and said knowledge must also lead to individual responsibility. `` It is the responsibility of each individual to learn about HIV and to treat those infected with HIV with respect and compassion. And it is the responsibility of infected individuals not to infect others,'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said in a message read by <PERSON> Miss </PERSON> <PERSON> Bailey </PERSON>. The pope's statement urged `` respect for all individuals'' and said `` the degree of civilization of societies may be judged by how civilization responds to the suffering of man.'' He said AIDS victims `` meet with my affection and are the subject of my prayers.''
