<HEAD>Illegal Aliens Travel Far For Amnesty</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 10 grafs to UPDATE with comments from INS director.
Picks up 6th graf pvs, `Illegal aliens ...'</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY13</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID S. MARTIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Basharat </PERSON> <PERSON> Mirza </PERSON>, an illegal alien from <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>, woke up well before dawn on the final day of an opportunity to keep his <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> dream alive. <PERSON> Mirza </PERSON> left <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> at 4:30 a.m. Wednesday and drove about 100 miles to a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Immigration and <ORGANIZATION> Naturalization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> office here. The 30-year-old <PERSON> Mirza </PERSON>, one of more than 1 million alien farm workers to apply for a work permit under a nationwide amnesty program that expired at midnight, said he chose the <LOCATION> Lima </LOCATION> office because <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> INS </ORGANIZATION> office was crowded with other applicants. `` Too much rush there. Too much people there,'' <PERSON> Mirza </PERSON> said. `` Not so many peoples here.'' The <ORGANIZATION> INS </ORGANIZATION> initially estimated that 600,000 farm workers would pay the $ 185 fee to apply under the sweeping program mandated by the 1986 immigration act. But by the deadline, 1.1 million to 1.2 million applications were taken, the agency said. <PERSON> Aaron </PERSON> <PERSON> Bodin </PERSON>, who heads the amnesty program for the <ORGANIZATION> INS </ORGANIZATION>, said today that the agency did not turn away any applicants who were waiting in line at <ORGANIZATION> INS </ORGANIZATION> offices at midnight. He said the agency believed many of those applying were not farm workers, but other aliens who missed a May 4 deadline for non-farm workers to apply for amnesty. `` I think it's because the standards of proof were so lenient that many aliens, feeling increasingly desperate because of employer sanctions -LRB- against hiring illegal aliens -RRB-, took advantage of that -LRB- farm program -RRB- to get legal status,'' <PERSON> Bodin </PERSON> said on `` This Morning'' on <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION>. `` We really do n't know how many people are truly eligible,'' he said. Those aliens whose applications are rejected `` are back where they were and the service takes no action. It's expected, however, because of the employer sanctions provisions making it illegal for employers to hire illegal aliens, these people will eventually be discouraged and return home of their own volition.'' Illegal aliens like <PERSON> Mirza </PERSON> came from as far away as <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> to the <ORGANIZATION> INS </ORGANIZATION> office in <LOCATION> Lima </LOCATION>, said <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Peterson </PERSON>, chief legalization officer in <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>, 20 miles northeast of here. In the weeks before the deadline, some applicants traveled by taxi from <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Peterson </PERSON> said. One arrived in a Mercedes equipped with a car phone. `` I did n't know there was so much money in farm work,'' <PERSON> Peterson </PERSON> joked. Under the first phase of the immigrant legalization program that ended May 4, temporary residency was granted to more than 1.7 million illegal aliens who proved continuous residency in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> since Jan. 1, 1982. Under agricultural phase, illegal aliens had to prove they harvested perishable crops for at least 90 days between May 1, 1985, and May 1, 1986. Those accepted will receive temporary residency status and eventually will be able to apply for permanent status. Effective today, agricultural employers now face fines up to $ 10,000 per illegal alien for hiring undocumented workers. Many applicants provided false documentation that cost them up to $ 3,000 in a desperate attempt to gain legal status, immigration officials across the country said. Ten applicants were arrested Wednesday at the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Orleans </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> INS </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> when they produced fake documents, and four others were arrested in connection with an organization that supplied illegal aliens with phony papers, <ORGANIZATION> INS </ORGANIZATION> officials said. In Liberal, <LOCATION> Kan. </LOCATION>, five people were arrested late Tuesday and early Wednesday for selling fraudulent employment letters to illegal aliens. More than half the applications under the program, or about 500,000, have come from <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, followed by <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> with about 10 percent and <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> with about 8 percent, officials said. Significant numbers were filed in the <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. At the <LOCATION> Lima </LOCATION> office, applicants from around the globe sat for hours, clutching paperwork and awaiting a chance to see an INS officer. Many spoke in their native tongues. One man wore a turban, others sported cowboy or baseball hats. By 7:30 p.m., about 125 people had met with <ORGANIZATION> INS </ORGANIZATION> officers, with 100 more to go before midnight and beyond, <PERSON> Peterson </PERSON> said. `` We'll take anyone in line at midnight,'' he said. <PERSON> Mirza </PERSON> said he qualified for amnesty by picking grapes and cherries in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>. `` Since -LRB- I was a -RRB- child, I have dream to come to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. Here, good money,'' he said. <PERSON> Mirza </PERSON> said he came to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> in 1984 via <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION> island of <LOCATION> Bimini </LOCATION> and an illegal boat landing in <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Hardev </PERSON> <PERSO