<HEAD>Police Recommend Prosecution In 1985 Jumbo Crash</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TETSUO JIMBO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Police today sought criminal charges against employees of <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Japan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lines </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Transport </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> after a three-year investigation into the cause of the world's worst single-plane crash. Police said the crash, in which 520 people died, was caused by the professional negligence of 20 people, including four <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> employees, 12 <ORGANIZATION> Japan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lines </ORGANIZATION> workers and four employees of the ministry of transport. The people accused of negligence were responsible for aircraft repairs, maintenance and inspection. It was the first time that criminal charges arising from a plane crash investigation have been sought against officials of the <ORGANIZATION> Transport </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION>, which is responsible for aviation safety. <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION>, the Seattle-based aircraft manufacturer, said in a statement it believed the accident did not involve a criminal act. `` <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> does not believe that criminal acts were committed by anyone and hopes that the district prosecutor's office also will conclude that there was no criminal conduct,'' the company said. <ORGANIZATION> Gunma </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Prefectural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Police </ORGANIZATION> handed results of the probe to the <ORGANIZATION> Maebashi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Prosecutor </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION>, which will decide whether to press charges for negligence, which is an offense under Japanese criminal law. The police said they were unable to question the four <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> employees. But they said documents confiscated from <ORGANIZATION> Japan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lines </ORGANIZATION> provided enough evidence to substantiate their involvement. The four reportedly supervised a repair of the aircraft in 1978 that was performed improperly. <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> sources said that police already have names of people who performed the repairs, but <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> employees have rejected repeated police requests for questioning. The <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 747 with 524 people aboard crashed into a mountain during a flight from <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Osaka </LOCATION> on Aug. 12, 1985, killing all but four on board. The police action highlights the different legal customs regarding air accidents and corporate criminal liability in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> is one of a few countries where criminal charges are sought against individuals responsible for airplane accidents, said <PERSON> Hiroshi </PERSON> <PERSON> Itakura </PERSON>, criminal law professor at <ORGANIZATION> Nihon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>. In the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, individuals involved in an airplane accident are usually granted criminal immunity in exchange for cooperating in investigations into the cause of an accident, <PERSON> Itakura </PERSON> said. `` The most important thing in an accident like this is to pinpoint the cause of the accident rather than to prosecute individuals,'' he said. `` But unlike the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, under Japanese criminal law corporations can not be charged for wrongdoing. `` In order to disclose causes of accidents, police have to seek criminal charges against individuals,'' he said. <PERSON> Susumu </PERSON> <PERSON> Yamachi </PERSON>, president of <ORGANIZATION> Japan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lines </ORGANIZATION>, said his company would take the matter seriously and continue its efforts to prevent the recurrence of such an tragic accident. <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> rejected Japanese allegations that the company had hindered the investigation, saying that it had cooperated with Japanese authorities. <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> sources said the company planned to respond to the police inquiry, but was unlikely to allow <LOCATION> Japanese </LOCATION> police to question individual employees. The airplane maker has disclosed that repairs it performed on the rear bulkhead, the metal partition that protects the pressurized cabin, of the aircraft after a minor accident in 1978 were faulty. The aircraft skidded on its tail during a rough landing in 1978 at <LOCATION> Osaka </LOCATION> <LOCATION> International </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION>, damaging its tail section, and underwent major repairs, according to <ORGANIZATION> JAL </ORGANIZATION>. A government report issued in 1987 concluded that improper repairs had accelerated metal fatigue, which caused the bulkhead to burst, blowing off part of the plane's tail fin and sending the jumbo jet out of control. The report accused the <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> JAL </ORGANIZATION>, and <ORGANIZATION> Transport </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> personnel of faulty repairs and inadequate inspection. Police said the accident could have been avoided if <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> had performed the repairs properly, if <ORGANIZATION> Japan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lines </ORGANIZATION> had checked the repairs adequately, and if the <ORGANIZATION> Transport </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> had inspected the aircraft properly. A group of relatives of passengers who died in the crash have presented signatures of 34,120 people to the <ORGANIZATION> Trasnport </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> requesting a criminal prosecution against <ORGANIZATION> JAL </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> JAL </ORGANIZATION> said about 70 percent of compensation negotiations have been settled. The company and <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> have agreed to share the cost of compensation to the victims' families and the four survivors of the crash, according to <ORGANIZATION> JAL </ORGANIZATION>.
