<HEAD>Survivor of Mountain Ordeal Walks to Safety After Friend Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GRANBY, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A man trapped in the Never Summer Mountains for five days walked to safety three days after his snowmobiling companion died of an apparent heart attack. <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Edson </PERSON>, 38, stumbled onto a logging road Wednesday morning where he was picked up by a truck driver. He and <PERSON> Ray </PERSON> <PERSON> Owens </PERSON>, 65, had traveled to the snow-whipped mountains 50 miles northwest of <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION> last Friday on an afternoon snowmobile outing. <PERSON> Owens </PERSON> died Sunday, and <PERSON> Edson </PERSON> waited two more days in vain to be rescued before walking out on his own. In recounting the ordeal from a hospital bed in <LOCATION> Granby </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Edson </PERSON> said the men's snowmobiles became mired the day they left in a high-country gulch 16 miles northwest of <LOCATION> Grand </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION>. `` When it became obvious the weather was not going to clear up and they were n't coming after us, I decided to go out the way we came,'' <PERSON> Edson </PERSON> said. Heavy winds had drifted snow over their tracks, and it took <PERSON> Edson </PERSON> nearly five hours to walk about two miles through snow up to 2 feet deep before he came to the logging road. <PERSON> Edson </PERSON>'s face and hands were black from sitting by a campfire in subzero weather. On his way out, <PERSON> Edson </PERSON> found snowmobile tracks indicating searchers had not been more than two miles from his campfire. <PERSON> Tony </PERSON> <PERSON> Winter </PERSON>, the logging truck driver, later led searchers to the spot where he found <PERSON> Edson </PERSON>, and the searchers followed <PERSON> Edson </PERSON>'s tracks back to his camp and recovered <PERSON> Owens </PERSON>' body. Freezing winds sent wind-chill factors to minus 30 degrees Fahrenheit in the area and blinding white-outs plagued would-be rescuers during the search. They had called off their ground search Tuesday night, after three days of searching. <PERSON> Edson </PERSON> said when they tried to free their machines Friday afternoon, `` that was when <PERSON> Ray </PERSON> had his first heart attack. He was feeling pretty poorly so we rested.'' Although they had brought along trail mix, cheese, crackers and fruit for their afternoon outing, neither man had any matches. <PERSON> Edson </PERSON> said they soaked a piece of cardboard in gasoline from a snowmobile, and cranked an engine, using a sparkplug to light the cardboard. `` The first night or two, when <PERSON> Ray </PERSON> was still alive, we traded turns taking care of the fire. After he died, I'd build the fire up and the smoke would blow in my face and choke me when it was getting low and I'd wake up again.'' Before he died Sunday, <PERSON> Owens </PERSON> wanted to try again to get out. `` He said, ` Let's go real slow,' but we did n't get more than 15 feet from the camp and he decided he was n't going,'' <PERSON> Edson </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Owens </PERSON> collapsed about noon Sunday and died. After <PERSON> Owens </PERSON>' death, <PERSON> Edson </PERSON> decided to `` stay where we were at, and wait to be rescued.'' At one point he heard a plane overhead, but the weather was too bad for the pilot to see them, even with a smoky fire. `` I'm tired and I'm thirsty but I feel fine,'' <PERSON> Edson </PERSON> said Wednesday night. `` I'm thankful for all the people who looked for us, and I'm sorry to have put them to so much trouble.''
