<HEAD>New Leader Wins Effort To Restore Family Name, Pakistani Democracy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN WILDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Benazir </PERSON> <PERSON> Bhutto </PERSON>'s selection as prime minister triumphantly ended an 11-year effort to restore her family name and Pakistani democracy. At 35, she also becomes one of the world's youngest heads of government and the first woman prime minister to lead a Moslem nation in modern times. Ms. <PERSON> Bhutto </PERSON>, who was educated at <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION> Oxford </LOCATION>, inherits the political mantle of her father, the late Prime Minister <PERSON> Zulfikar </PERSON> <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> <PERSON> Bhutto </PERSON>, who was ousted by Gen. <PERSON> Mohammed </PERSON> <PERSON> Zia </PERSON> <PERSON> ul-Haq </PERSON> in a 1977 coup and hanged two years later. <PERSON> Zia </PERSON>'s death in an Aug. 17 plane crash made Ms. <PERSON> Bhutto </PERSON>, who had pledged to restore democracy, the nation's only nationally recognized political leader. Although a daughter of affluence, Ms. <PERSON> Bhutto </PERSON>'s appeal lies mainly among the poor masses of this country's 107 million people. They are the strength of her left-leaning <ORGANIZATION> Pakistan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, which captured the most seats in the Nov. 16 National Assembly elections. Ms. <PERSON> Bhutto </PERSON> drew massive, adoring crowds during her campaign for the country's first free elections since her father's death. Mindful of Moslem and local custom, she always is clad in traditional clothes with a scarf draped over her head. The poised and articulate leader, who speaks English fluently, shocked her Western friendsby consenting to an arranged marriage last December with <LOCATION> Karachi </LOCATION> businessman <PERSON> Asif </PERSON> <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> <PERSON> Zardari </PERSON>. Ms. <PERSON> Bhutto </PERSON>, who has kept her maiden name, was groomed for politics by her doting father as the eldest of his four children. He sent her to study government and politics at <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> then at <LOCATION> Oxford </LOCATION>. It was at the British university that she tasted her first political success when she was elected president of the prestigious <ORGANIZATION> Oxford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> debating society in 1976. The prime minister's post is Ms. <PERSON> Bhutto </PERSON> first paying job. Her only previous employment began in early 1977 as a non-paid trainee in the <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION>. It was short-lived, however, as <PERSON> Zia </PERSON> toppled her father's government a few months later on the pretext that elections that year were rigged <PERSON> Bhutto </PERSON> was hanged in 1979 after his conviction for helping plot the murder of a political foe, a charge his family has denied. Despite years of detention and foreign exile during <PERSON> Zia </PERSON>'s authoritarian rule, Ms. <PERSON> Bhutto </PERSON> and her mother, <PERSON> Nusrat </PERSON>, kept the party alive as <PERSON> Zia </PERSON>'s disenfranchised opposition Ms. <PERSON> Bhutto </PERSON>'s party critics claim she has inherited her father's domineering ego but has renounced his socialist ideals Her supporters say that with <PERSON> Zia </PERSON> gone, she is <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>'s only nationally recognized political leader and a unifying force in the country's volatile ethnic mosaic. Her party commands 105 votes in the 237-seat <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION>, and Ms. <PERSON> Bhutto </PERSON> says she has enough support from independents and minor parties to command a majority. Ms. <PERSON> Bhutto </PERSON> espouses prosperity for the poor but has appeased the business community with promises of a market-oriented economy, and the military by pledging to continue <PERSON> Zia </PERSON>'s staunch backing with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> of Moslem anti-communist rebels in neighboring <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>. She started her election campaign in late October, following the Sept. 21 birth of her first child, a son named <PERSON> Bilawal </PERSON>. Ms. <PERSON> Bhutto </PERSON> rarely has appeared with her husband in public and has not yet allowed public photographs of their baby.
