<HEAD>Authorities Seek Clues In Blast That Killed Six Firefighters</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Ammonium nitrate that exploded during an arson fire and killed six firemen had been mixed with other compounds that made it far more explosive than usual, police say. A reward for information on the arsonists has reached $ 35,000 with an anonymous donor's offer of $ 25,000, and donations are pouring in for the victims' families, city officials said. Firefighters from across the nation and <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> are expected at a memorial service. Officials initially thought that only ammonium nitrate, considered one of the milder and more stable explosives, had been stored in two trailers that blew up early Tuesday at a highway construction site. But the ammonium nitrate had been mixed with diesel fuel, pink dye and powdered aluminum to form `` <PERSON> Maynes </PERSON> mix,'' a blasting agent usually detonated by a small amount of dynamite, police said. The mixture explains why the blasts were powerful enough to kill the firefighters, demolish two firetrucks and create a shock wave that broke windows up to 10 miles away and was heard up to 40 miles away. `` All it requires is a heat source'' to detonate, said police Sgt. <PERSON> Gregory </PERSON> <PERSON> Mills </PERSON>. <PERSON> Mills </PERSON> said there were no significant developments Wednesday in the arson investigation. Officials announced a $ 35,000 reward for information on suspects in the fire. <PERSON> Sandy </PERSON> <PERSON> Berkley </PERSON>, wife of Mayor <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Berkley </PERSON> who is on a trade mission in the <LOCATION> Far </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION>, said a donor who wishes to remain anonymous had given $ 25,000 toward the reward fund. An additional $ 5,000 came from the <ORGANIZATION> Heavy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Equipment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Construction </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> and $ 5,000 from the Arson Hotline. Donations also have been pouring into <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZ