announcing plans for meeting regional officials. Pickup 8th graf
pvs, ``Azerbaijan and...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> newspaper Pravda today said 28 people have been killed in two weeks ofethnic violence in the republics of <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION>. Kremlin leaders issued an urgent appeal for calm. Official reports said thousands of people were fleeing the unrest. `` We are losing our people,'' <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Mikhailov </PERSON> was quoted as saying in Pravda. The situation in the southern region remained tense, with mass meetings in many towns in <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION> despite the presence of Soviet troops, tanks and a strict curfew, <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION> Interior Minister <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Mamedov </PERSON> said. Authorities have confiscated homemade pistols, sawed-off rifles and explosives from young people in <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Mikhailov </PERSON> said. He said said the death toll includes Armenians, Azerbaijanis, a Russian, a Byelorussian and a Ukrainian. In <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>, at the end of a three-day conference of the Supreme Soviet, the <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> leadership announced plans for the parliament's Presidium, the highest state executive body, to hold a meeting of party, state and social organizations with national deputies from <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION> and the disputed <LOCATION> Nagorno-Karabakh </LOCATION> region `` The Supreme Soviet appeals to workers of <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION> to display wisdom and restraint,'' said a directive signed by President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> that called for the meeting. <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION>, two southern 