<HEAD>Centralia Editor and Publisher Was 60</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CENTRALIA, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Verne </PERSON> <PERSON> Joy </PERSON>, editor and publisher of the <ORGANIZATION> Centralia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Evening </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sunday </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sentinel </ORGANIZATION> since 1964, died today after a brief illness. He was 60. Joy, who died at <LOCATION> Barnes </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hospital </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Louis </LOCATION>, was the fourth generation of the <PERSON> Joy </PERSON> family to serve as editor and publisher of the 126-year-old newspaper in southern <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>. Born in <LOCATION> Centralia </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Joy </PERSON> attended <ORGANIZATION> Hill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Pottstown </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pa </LOCATION>. He was a 1950 graduate of <ORGANIZATION> Cornell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> and served two years with the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>. Following his Korean duty, <PERSON> Joy </PERSON> served 1 -LCB- years as an intern at the <ORGANIZATION> Rockford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Evening </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> and six months at <ORGANIZATION> Illinois </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Daily </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Newspaper </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Markets </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Springfield </LOCATION>. He returned to <LOCATION> Centralia </LOCATION> in 1955 to work under his grandfather, editor and publisher <PERSON> Verne </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Joy </PERSON>, and also played a key role in the building of the city's <ORGANIZATION> Carillon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tower </ORGANIZATION> and adjoining Tower Park. Survivors include his wife, <PERSON> Judith </PERSON>, and son, <PERSON> Thomas </PERS