<HEAD>Former Police Chief Charged With Nepotism</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOMINY, Okla (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A misdemeanor charge of nepotism is the only charge that came out of an investigation of the town's former police chief, a black man who charged racial bias after he was fired amid allegations of misconduct. The nepotism charge was filed against former chief <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Crawford </PERSON>, 45, who had been accused of sexually harassing female employees. <PERSON> Crawford </PERSON> is accused of appointing a sister-in-law as a temporary police department employee Sept. 7. He was fired Oct. 6, and his sister-in-law no longer works in the department. District Attorney <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Stuart </PERSON> said Tuesday that state law prohibits an elected official from appointing or hiring any person related to him by marriage or blood within the third degree. The charge carries a fine of between $ 100 and $ 1,000 and forfeiture of office. Allegations against <PERSON> Crawford </PERSON> had included sexual involvement with dispatchers and juveniles, sexual harassment of other female employees, preferential treatment for some residents and harsh handling of others. One former dispatcher has filed a paternity suit against him. <PERSON> Crawford </PERSON> said city officials who opposed having a black chief conspired to oust him, using allegations that he had affairs with white police dispatchers to raise the ire of the all-white City Council. The town of 3,000 people has about 150 blacks. <PERSON> Stuart </PERSON> issued a statement saying the nearly two-month investigation by his office and the <ORGANIZATION> Oklahoma </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Investigation </ORGANIZATION> `` failed to produce substantiated evidence, or victims who desired to pursue criminal charges.'' He said matters alleged to have occurred more than three years ago were not investigated because the statute of limitations had expired. <PERSON> Stuart </P