<HEAD>Yugoslavia Rejects Australian Ultimatum To Turn Over Consulate
Guard</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 11 grafs to UPDATE with Yugoslavia rejecting
ultimatum, other details. Pickup 10th graf pvs, ``Yugoslav
Ambassador...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD BILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SYDNEY, Australia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION> said today it will close the Yugoslav Consulate and expel its staff if authorities there do n't turn over a security guard who shot a teen-age demonstrator <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION> rejected the demand. The moves were the latest in a diplomatic wrangle over the wounding of the youth on Sunday and <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>'s refusal to apologize formally for the shooting at its consulate in <LOCATION> Sydney </LOCATION>. In a statement carried by the official <ORGANIZATION> Tanjug </ORGANIZATION> news agency in <LOCATION> Belgrade </LOCATION>, the Yugoslav government said Australian officials `` failed to undertake measures to protect our consulate'' from attackers. The security guard `` had no choice but shooting into the air to warn Australian organs ... that lives and security of workers in the consulate and their families were directly imperiled,'' the statement said. The statement was in response to one issued earlier by Foreign Minister <PERSON> Gareth </PERSON> <PERSON> Evans </PERSON> saying the Australian government had sufficient evidence to prosecute the security guard who fired the gun. <PERSON> Evans </PERSON> demanded that the guard, identified as <PERSON> Matijas </PERSON> <PERSON> Zoran </PERSON>, be handed over to police by 6 p.m. Friday or `` the Australian government will immediately close the consulate-general.'' About 1,500 people protested at the consulate on Sunday, Yugoslav National Day. Police said a security guard fired on hundreds of demonstrators when several Croatian youths began climbing the walls. <PERSON> Jospeh </PERSON> <PERSON> Tokic </PERSON>, 16, was shot in the throat and was in stable condition at a <LOCATION> Sydney </LOCATION> hospital. Croatians are among several ethnic groups in <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>. About 200,000 Yugoslavs live in <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Tanjug </ORGANIZATION> said the <LOCATION> Yugoslav </LOCATION> government referred to the demonstrators as Ustashas, Croatian fascists who allied with <ORGANIZATION> Nazi </ORGANIZATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> against <LOCATION> Yugoslav </LOCATION> resistance forces during World War II. Yugoslav Ambassador <PERSON> Boris </PERSON> <PERSON> Cizelj </PERSON> allowed police to question the guard after consulting with his government in <LOCATION> Belgrade </LOCATION>. But he insisted the interview be conducted inside the consulate and in the presence of the consul-general. He said <PERSON> Zoran </PERSON> would not leave the country until police complete their investigation. The <LOCATION> Belgrade </LOCATION> government lodged an official protest over what it called a lack of police protection during the demonstration.
