<HEAD>Fernald Plant to Lay Off 350 Workers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The federal government's Fernald uranium-processing plant will lay off about 350 employees soon because of decreased demand for the enriched uranium it produces, officials announced today. The layoff, the second since April at the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s Feed Materials Production Center, will include both management and production-line employees and could begin before Christmas, said <PERSON> Pete </PERSON> <PERSON> Kelley </PERSON>, a spokesman for the plant's operator, <ORGANIZATION> Westinghouse </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Materials </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>. Workers to be affected will be notified Dec. 9, he said. <PERSON> Kelley </PERSON> said the layoffs have nothing to do with a strike by 625 unionized production workers, which has idled the plant since Oct. 7. Westinghouse Materials laid off 70 employees at the government plant in April because of declining orders for uranium and said then that another layoff was likely later this year. `` They would have occurred anyway, because the production is down substantially for this fiscal year from last,'' <PERSON> Kelley </PERSON> said. The plant's operating budget last year was $ 145 million but was cut to $ 107 million this year, he said. <ORGANIZATION> Westinghouse </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Materials </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> said it will provide affected employees with job counseling, asistance with resume writing, interview skills training and a placement center. The plant now employs about 1,500 people. It has supplied uranium recently for the <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s Rocky Flats plant in <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Hanford </LOCATION> reactors in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> state, the <LOCATION> Savannah </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> plant in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Oak </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ridge </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tenn. </LOCATION>, nuclear complex. The <LOCATION> Savannah </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> reactors are shut down because of problems there, and the Rocky Flats plant reportedly is under consideration for eventual closure by the <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>. The Fernald plant, located 18 miles northwest of <LOCATION> Cincinnati </LOCATION>, has been under heavy criticism in recent years. The Energy Department recently admitted that the plant has released at least 300,000 pounds of radioactive uranium dust into the atmosphere during its 37 years of operation.
