<FIRST>r i AM-Gandhi-Assassins     12-01 0429</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Gandhi-Assassins,0444</SECOND>
<HEAD>Executions Stayed For Sikhs Convicted In Gandhi Assassination</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RAJU GOPALAKRISHNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> on Thursday blocked the executions of two Sikhs condemned to death for the 1984 assassination of Prime Minister <PERSON> Indira </PERSON> <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON>, news reports said. A panel of five justices granted a stay of execution for <PERSON> Satwant </PERSON> <PERSON> Singh </PERSON>, a guard who shot Mrs. <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON>, and <PERSON> Kehar </PERSON> <PERSON> Singh </PERSON>, convicted of conspiracy. The two were scheduled to hang Friday but the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> agreed to stay the execution until Tuesday in order to hear arguments on a petition filed by <PERSON> Kehar </PERSON> <PERSON> Singh </PERSON>'s son. They are not related. Members of the Sikh faith use the name <PERSON> Singh </PERSON>, which means lion. The petition challenges President <PERSON> Ramaswamy </PERSON> <PERSON> Venkataraman </PERSON>'s refusal to grant clemency to his father without reviewing the merits of the case, <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> India </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trust </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> India </ORGANIZATION> reported <PERSON> Venkataraman </PERSON> last week said he could not go into the merits of a case already decided by the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>. The petition filed by <PERSON> Rajinder </PERSON> <PERSON> Singh </PERSON>, however, contends the Constitution gives the president such powers, the news agencies said. The judges also stayed <PERSON> Satwant </PERSON> <PERSON> Singh </PERSON>'s execution after his lawyer appealed against another high court decision dismissing his appeals earlier in the day. Two Sikh bodyguards, <PERSON> Satwant </PERSON> <PERSON> Singh </PERSON> and <PERSON> Beant </PERSON> <PERSON> Singh </PERSON>, shot Mrs. <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON> in the garden of her residence on Oct. 31, 1984. She was apparently killed in retaliation for an army raid she ordered four months earlier to rout militants from the <ORGANIZATION> Golden </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Temple </ORGANIZATION>, the Sikhs' holiest shrine. More than 1,200 people died, most of them Sikhs. <PERSON> Beant </PERSON> <PERSON> Singh </PERSON> was killed in a shootout with other security guards and is revered as a martyr by many militant Sikhs. <PERSON> Kehar </PERSON> <PERSON> Singh </PERSON>, <PERSON> Beant </PERSON>'s uncle, was arrested a month later and charged with helping to plot Mrs. <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON>'s murder, which triggered anti-Sikh riots across northern <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> by members of the majority Hindu religion. More than 2,700 people died, nearly all of them Sikhs. Sikh violence since then has escalated. More than 2,300 people have died this year alone in northern <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION> state, where Sikhs are fighting for an independent homeland. Authorities had ordered increased security in the capital and in <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION>, fearing the executions could trigger a new outbreak of communal violence. <PERSON> Kehar </PERSON> <PERSON> Singh </PERSON>, 54, and <PERSON> Satwant </PERSON> <PERSON> Singh </PERSON>, 30, have been held at the maximum-security Tihar Central Jail in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Delhi </LOCATION> since their arrests in 1984. Their eight-month trial ended on Jan. 22, 1986. The convictions and death sentences were subsequently upheld by an appeals court and by the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>.
