<SECOND>PM-Mafia Sweep,0372</SECOND>
<HEAD>Italian, U.S. Authorities Cooperate in Drug Sweep</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Italy-Mafia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PALERMO, Sicily (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Police arrested members of the Mafia in cities throughout <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> today as a similar sweep targeting drug-trafficking rings took place in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> ANSA </ORGANIZATION> news agency said authorities involved in operation `` Iron Tower'' began arresting people during the night in <LOCATION> Palermo </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Bologna </ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION> Florence </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> Director <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Sessions </PERSON>, in a statement released in <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> today, said drug charges have been filed against 75 people in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and 133 people in <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>. He said the arrests were under way in nine unspecified Italian cities and in <LOCATION> Baltimore </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Buffalo </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Newark </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>; and <LOCATION> Rockford </LOCATION>, Ill. The Italian news agency <ORGANIZATION> ANSA </ORGANIZATION> said the people named in the Italian arrest warrants were members of the Satola, <PERSON> Gambino </PERSON> and <PERSON> Inzerillo </PERSON> crime families in <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. The state-run RAI-TV said several top Mafia figures were among those arrested. Italian news agencies said the drug raids resulted from an investigation that stemmed from the `` Pizza Connection'' international drug ring that sold $ 1.6 billion of heroin, mostly through pizzerias in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. A <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> court convicted 18 people in connection with that ring and Italian prosecutors indicted 28 people for their alleged involvement. <ORGANIZATION> ANSA </ORGANIZATION> and the Italian news agency <ORGANIZATION> AGI </ORGANIZATION> said the investigation that led to today's raids was triggered by the arrest of women drug couriers at airports in <LOCATION> Palermo </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> two years ago. It said the women were paid about $ 7,800 for every 2.2 pounds of heroin they smuggled from <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> inside money belts. <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> agents used court-authorized wiretaps, physical surveillance and heroin and cocaine buys to develop the evidence that led to the arrests in <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, Sessions said. He said the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> also discovered cocaine was being sent from <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> to a laboratory 300 miles north of <LOCATION> Madrid </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>, to be processed and sent to <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>. In <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>, the cocaine was then exchanged for heroin that was smuggled into the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. He said the information led to arrests in <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>.
