<FIRST>r i AM-NATO     12-01 0472</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-NATO,0491</SECOND>
<HEAD>NATO Defense Ministers Urge U.S. Allies to Play Greater Role</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> defense ministers Thursday urged <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> allies to boost defense spending, upgrade military equipment and play a greater role in maintaining a strong Western alliance. The recommendations came in a `` burden-sharing'' report that responds to criticism from <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> congressman who argue the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is picking up too much of the defense tab. Ministers adopted the report at the start of a two-day meeting. The report acknowledged `` significant differences between individual national contributions.'' But it contended countries such as <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> bear high social costs because of 400,000 foreign troops stationed there. West German Defense Minister <PERSON> Rupert </PERSON> <PERSON> Scholz </PERSON> said the review on his country was `` rather positive. I did n't expect it any other way.'' <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> critics have suggested the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> withdraw some of its 326,000 troops stationed in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> if the Europeans do not pay more. `` As the alliance approaches its 40th anniversary, its strength and cohesion remain as firm as ever, with continuing major contributions being made by both the European and <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> pillars,'' the report said. But it noted both rich and poor countries have earmarked for defense less and less as a percentage of total economic activity or gross domestic product. <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Luxembourg </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION> were singled out for maintaining or increasing slightly their levels of defense spending. Allocating money for defense was crucial. `` But making available people and space, accepting limitations in personal freedom or the quality of life, braving internal or external tensions, and different degrees of exposure or vulnerability are by no means less important elements of the overall burden,'' the report said. It estimated the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> tagged an average 5.98 percent of its economic output to defense from 1983 to 1987. Well ahead was <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION>, which spent 6.52 percent. <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> devoted 5.01 percent of its GDP to defense; <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION> averaged 4 percent, and <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> 3.2 percent. Others were: <LOCATION> Belgium </LOCATION>, 3.26 percent; <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, 2.17 percent; <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION>, 2.2 percent; <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>, 2.16 percent; <LOCATION> Luxembourg </LOCATION>, 1.18 percent; <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION>, 3.32 percent; <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION>, 2.93 percent; <LOCATION> Portugal </LOCATION>, 3.22 percent; and <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>, 2.37 percent. <LOCATION> Iceland </LOCATION> was not included in the table. All <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION>'s 16 nations except <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION> are members of the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Planning </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, which approved the report. The report praised the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration for `` an exceptional and sustained effort to modernize and upgrade all aspects of its armed forces.'' But it said the defense spending surge `` seems to have come to an end and is likely to be followed by a period of stabilization.'' European countries, it said, provide 90 percent of the manpower, 80 percent of combat aircraft, 70 percent of tanks and 80 percent of artillery in the alliance. But it urged many European members and <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> to make bigger contributions.
