sued by anti-Mafia magistrate <PERSON> Giovanne </PERSON> <PERSON> Falcone </PERSON>. It said all the people named in the warrants were members of the <PERSON> Spatola </PERSON>, <PERSON> Gambino </PERSON> and <PERSON> Inzerillo </PERSON> crime families in <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. The state-run RAI-TV said Italian authorities, with the help of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> investigators, arrested several top Mafia figures. It said 300 policemen, helped by helicopters and dogs, were reportedly employed in the sweep. As one part of the investigation, the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> said it developed information that cocaine was being sent from <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> to a laboratory 300 miles north of <LOCATION> Madrid </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>. There the cocaine was processed and sent to <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> and exchanged for heroin that was shipped to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> told Spanish and Italian authorities about the exchange and arrests were subsequently made in <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> AGI </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> ANSA </ORGANIZATION> said the probe that led to the raids began after the arrest of women drug couriers at airports in <LOCATION> Palermo </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> two years ago. It said the women were paid $ 7,800 for every two pounds of heroin they smuggled from <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> inside money belts.
