<HEAD>One Man Dead in Pier Fire</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MORRO BAY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A fire burned an oil-soaked pier today, killing one man and destroying at least 11 boats and two cars, authorities said. A tower of black smoke hung over the area, and some people were evacuated. The dead man was asleep in his boat when the fire broke out and spread to his vessel, said <ORGANIZATION> Morro </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bay </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fire </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> Harpster </PERSON>. At least two other people were injured in the early morning blaze. Authorities ordered the evacuation of an area downwind from the fire for about a quarter-mile after hearing reports that the pier was treated with creosote, a carcinogenic substance. The waterfront of this town 175 miles northwest of <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> is lined with restaurants and souvenir shops along a strip known as the embarcadero. The pier that burned was known as the T Pier because of its shape. <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Morgan </PERSON> and his wife, <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Ann </PERSON>, said they saw the fire break out and after <PERSON> Morgan </PERSON> called the Fire Department they returned to the pier to knock on boats and awaken the live-aboard occupants. Shortly afterward, <PERSON> Morgan </PERSON> said, `` The fire just went whoosh'' and engulfed the pier off the city's waterfront. `` There's a huge cloud of dark, oily smoke,'' said <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> Peterson </PERSON> of radio station <ORGANIZATION> KSLY </ORGANIZATION>. `` The pier is an old pier and soaked with oil from over the years. It's a stubborn fire.'' The crew of the <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> cutter Point Winslow towed the burning boats away from the pier. The boats, both fishing and pleasure craft, were left burning as firefighters turned their attention to controlling the pier blaze. <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZ