<HEAD>Dissident Speaks Out 10 Years After Quashed Democracy Movement</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An accountant who was jailed four years for criticizing the ruling <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> has appealed to the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rights </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> to intercede on behalf of fellow dissidents still in prison. <PERSON> Ren </PERSON> <PERSON> Wanding </PERSON> also renewed his call first made a decade ago that the party allow the <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> people to decide in free elections who should rule them. `` I say what everything thinks,'' <PERSON> Ren </PERSON> said in an interview Thursday marked by a frankness rarely seen in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s tightly controlled political atmosphere. `` The people are not satisfied. When the time is ready they will stand up,'' he said. `` I have no plans to organize an uprising. It's a historical necessity. <PERSON> Ren </PERSON>, 44, helped lead the 1978-79 <ORGANIZATION> Democracy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wall </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Movement </ORGANIZATION>, a brief thaw during which authorities tolerated unprecedented calls for multiparty democracy. He and dozens of other dissidents were imprisoned in 1979 as counterrevolutionaries. <PERSON> Ren </PERSON>, who said he was never given a trial, was released in 1983 after four years of `` education by labor,'' including two years in solitary confinement. He said he was speaking out after nearly a decade of silence in order to mark the movement's anniversary and draw attention to colleagues still in jail. `` If the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rights </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> and international society do not expose the human rights violations of their members ... this will promote evil and do damage to justice and the lofty purpose of the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION>,'' <PERSON> Ren </PERSON> wrote to the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION>. He urged the world community to investigate the conditions of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s jailed dissidents. Human rights groups, he wrote, should ask, `` Are they dressed warmly in prison, and are they bothered by flies in summer? `` What is their nutrition and medical treatment like? Are these people still beaten in prison? Are they required to donate blood even though they suffer from poor nutrition? Are they still given meat and canned food that has gone bad? ... Are they still allowed out just once every month or two months, and given only a minute or two for a trip to the toilet?'' `` Having been in prison, I am familiar with the suffering,'' <PERSON> Ren </PERSON> said in the interview. He said he was held in solitary confinement for two years, and was allowed books only after the first year. <PERSON> Ren </PERSON> also issued a statement this week to the foreign media urging foreign businesses to demand <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> improve its human rights policy before investing. The Democracy Wall Movement began with a few pro-democracy posters plastered on a brick wall in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>. Encouraged by reformist statements by top leader <PERSON> Deng </PERSON> <PERSON> Xiaoping </PERSON>, students and workers put hundreds more posters on the wall and similar walls in other cities. Home-printed magazines circulated openly demanding rule by law, multi-party elections and an end to party privileges. <PERSON> Ren </PERSON>, along with more than a dozen friends, edited a journal called <ORGANIZATION> Chinese </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rights </ORGANIZATION>, mimeographing hundreds of copies in their homes. By 1979, however, <PERSON> Deng </PERSON> had consolidated his hold over leftists in the party and cracked down on the democracy movement. More than a dozen of its leaders remain jailed, <PERSON> Ren </PERSON> said. The best known is <PERSON> Wei </PERSON> <PERSON> Jingsheng </PERSON>, who wrote an impassioned plea for democracy as a `` fifth modernization'' to go along with the official program of modernizing agriculture, industry, science and the military. Last year, <ORGANIZATION> Amnesty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> said it had unconfirmed reports <PERSON> Wei </PERSON> had died in prison, but <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> denied it. <PERSON> Ren </PERSON> said he had no direct information on <PERSON> Wei </PERSON> but believed him to be at a labor camp in western <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Qinghai </LOCATION> province. Other activists in the <ORGANIZATION> Democracy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wall </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Movement </ORGANIZATION> have remained silent since. Thousands of students in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> and other cities joined in pro-democracy marches in the winter of 1986-87, but no nationally renowned leaders emerged and the demonstrations subsided under a government crackdown. Since then, the only dissident who has openly criticized Marxism and one-party rule is <PERSON> Fang </PERSON> <PERSON> Lizhi </PERSON>, an astrophysicist who says his fame gives him some protection from government retribution. He was expelled from the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> in 1987 for allegedly having helped incite the student protests. <PERSON> Ren </PERSON> said he also has no plans to form an opposition, but will continue to speak out. `` How can I not speak?'' <PERSON> Ren </PERSON> said. `` I ca n't be afraid of arrest, if I am I ca n't do anything. If they arrest me, they arrest me.''
