<HEAD>Marcos: Nobody's Proved Anything Against Him</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE LINDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Former <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> President <PERSON> Ferdinand </PERSON> <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON>, charged with conspiring to steal more than $ 100 million from his homeland, writes in a journal to be published this month that he is being unfairly judged. <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON>, whose lawyers claim he's too ill to stand trial or even to travel from his exile home in <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION>, writes his defense in the winter issue of <ORGANIZATION> Orbis </ORGANIZATION>, to be distributed Dec. 28 by the <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Policy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>, a <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> think tank. An advance copy of the article was made available to The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> insists in the six-page, 2,500-word essay that he did n't raid the treasury of more than $ 5 billion during the 21 years he led the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> until his ouster in 1986, and he did n't allow friends to siphon off huge sums `` The fact is that none of these charges, which are criminal in character, has been made subject to judicial scrutiny,'' <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> wrote. `` Many of the so-called <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> cronies are in the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> today. They are within the reach of the present administration in <LOCATION> Manila </LOCATION>. Although presumably possessed of all the evidence necessary to establish their guilt, the Aquino administration has not prosecuted any of these putative malefactors. `` Private property has been seized; moral declamations have been broadcast; but not one single case has been brought before a court of law. With criminals in such abundance, whose guilt is so evident, one might have expected that at least one of them would have had to face prosecution by this time.'' <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> wrote that he has asked the government in <LOCATION> Manila </LOCATION> to allow him to return and `` afford me the opportunity to face my accusers -LRB- but -RRB- it has steadfastly refused my demand for a day in court.'' <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON>' article was in response to one written in the last issue of <ORGANIZATION> Orbis </ORGANIZATION>, distributed in September, by <PERSON> Theodore </PERSON> <PERSON> Friend </PERSON>, former president of <ORGANIZATION> Swarthmore </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> and currently head of <ORGANIZATION> Eisenhower </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fellowships </ORGANIZATION>. Friend accused <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> of wrecking the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> politically and economically through corruption and murder.. <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> said the `` omnibus charges repeated by Friend -LRB- that -RRB- I am personally responsible for the murder of political opponents, and the massive derogation of human rights in the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> merit little further comment'' because his request to return and be subject to his country's courts had been rejected `` To date, the authorities in <LOCATION> Manila </LOCATION> have refused my request, have failed to indict, and display a singular unwillingness to prosecute,'' <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> wrote. Friend, in an answer to <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> in the same <ORGANIZATION> Orbis </ORGANIZATION>, called him an astute lawyer `` who shielded himself with legalisms, many of them contrived.'' He also said 39 civil suits against him in the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> seek a total of $ 96.17 billion, and that criminal suits also are pending there. `` <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> used his regime as a means to preserve and enhance his own political power; as a means to engorge his friends; and as a means to enrich his family and himself _ not by ` peculations' but by systematic parasitic robbery,'' Friend wrote. <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON>, who rejected every suggestion he was guilty of anything, said <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> intervention into <LOCATION> Philippine </LOCATION> affairs that led to his ouster and the election of <PERSON> Corazon </PERSON> <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> as president backfired. `` The strangest feature of all this is that not only have <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> interests now been placed in serious jeopardy, but all the charges that made my administration a pariah among policy makers in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> have recently resurfaced as charges against the present regime,'' <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> wrote. <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> and his wife, <PERSON> Imelda </PERSON>, were indicted Oct. 21 in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> on federal criminal racketeering charges accusing them of plundering the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION>' treasury and stashing much of the money in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. Mrs. <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> pleaded innocent to the charges Oct. 31 in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> and was released on $ 5 million bail. Defense lawyers contend <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> is too frail to make the 10-hour flight to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> for arraignment or trial. A court-appointed physician decided in late November that <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> is healthy enough to face charges in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>.
