<HEAD>Mrs. Bush Tops Off National Christmas Tree</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> ascended 35 feet aboard a bumpy hydraulic boom on Thursday and placed the crowning ornament atop the National Christmas Tree, a <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION> blue spruce just beyond the back fence of the house she'll move into next month. It was the eighth consecutive year the wife of the vice president has performed that task, and one she apparently does n't want to give up when husband <PERSON> George </PERSON>'s title is shortened. `` It's the only thing I've done more than anyone else,'' she told a guest in a reception line afterwards. `` I love it.'' To a separate guest she said `` I would be offended if someone else did it.'' President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> is to light the live national tree for his last time Dec. 15, after which a pageant featuring 57 trees, each decorated with ornaments from a different state or territory, will be opened. More than 700,000 people visited the exhibit last year. The tree was transplanted to its spot on the Ellipse, a park betwen the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and the <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> Monument, in 1978 after two earlier trees died before taking root. Two classes of <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> first-graders applauded and cheered as Mrs. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> had an animated chat with puppet dinosaurs <PERSON> Rex </PERSON> and <PERSON> Rita </PERSON> <PERSON> Readasaurus </PERSON> and Pageant Director <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Riley </PERSON> as they rode the boom basket skyward. `` It was a shakey ride,'' said <PERSON> Lynn </PERSON> <PERSON> Hippen </PERSON> who was crouched down in the boom box with puppet designer <PERSON> Brad </PERSON> <PERSON> Williams </PERSON>, `` but everyone maintained their balance and poise.'' The puppets, <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> said, were `` hatched'' at the National Zoo in May to promote the national Reading is Fundamental program. He said they and Mrs. <PERS