<FIRST>r i AM-Germany-Nuclear     12-01 0764</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Germany-Nuclear,0791</SECOND>
<HEAD>Berlin Marks 50 Years of Nuclear Fission</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN COSTELLOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Fifty years ago, German scientists <PERSON> Otto </PERSON> <PERSON> Hahn </PERSON> and <PERSON> Fritz </PERSON> <PERSON> Strassmann </PERSON> discovered nuclear fission, a breakthrough that led to the atom bomb and nuclear energy. On Thursday, <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> held the first of several events marking the fateful work. The discovery by <PERSON> Hahn </PERSON> and <PERSON> Strassmann </PERSON> also was intertwined with the Nazi era. <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Speer </PERSON>, a former top aide to <PERSON> Adolf </PERSON> <PERSON> Hitler </PERSON>, strongly implied that <PERSON> Hahn </PERSON> was one of a group of German scientists seeking ways to build an atomic bomb before the Americans beat them to it. <PERSON> Hahn </PERSON>, a physicist and chemist who won the 1944 Nobel Prize in chemistry for his discovery, worked closely with a Jewish colleague forced into exile by the <ORGANIZATION> Nazis </ORGANIZATION>. The December 1938 work at the <ORGANIZATION> Kaiser </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wilhelm </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chemistry </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> also represented one of the many feats of the proud German scientific tradition. On Thursday, scientists and officials of the <ORGANIZATION> Technical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Berlin </ORGANIZATION> outlined the impact of <PERSON> Strassmann </PERSON>'s and <PERSON> Hahn </PERSON>'s discovery at an exhibition of models, photographs and scientific equipment documenting the work `` The development of nuclear physics and its technology has found interest among the public like no other discovery,'' said <PERSON> Ulrich </PERSON> <PERSON> Steinmueller </PERSON>, vice president of the <ORGANIZATION> Technical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. `` The technology carries implicitly in its use _ both in war and peace _ a threat for mankind,'' <PERSON> Steinmueller </PERSON> said. `` The well-founded worries and fears of people give scientists a challenge to be aware of their responsibilities to society.'' West Germans have been sensitive to some of the end results of <PERSON> Hahn </PERSON> and <PERSON> Strassmann </PERSON>'s discovery: the stationing of nuclear rockets on their soil and the fallout from the <LOCATION> Chernobyl </LOCATION> nuclear accident in 1986 in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. `` That day 50 years ago in <LOCATION> Dahlem </LOCATION> -LRB- the <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> district where the discovery took place -RRB- must also be remembered along with the day of <LOCATION> Hiroshima </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Nagasaki </LOCATION> and the day of Chernobyl,'' <PERSON> Steinmueller </PERSON> told the news conference at the <ORGANIZATION> Technical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Steinmueller </PERSON> added that the peaceful use of nuclear energy `` leaves open more problems than it solves.'' <PERSON> Hahn </PERSON> and <PERSON> Strassmann </PERSON> found that bombarding the uranium atom with neutrons leads to its splitting. At first, they were unsure of what they had discovered. From her exile in <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION>, Jewish colleague <PERSON> Lise </PERSON> <PERSON> Meitner </PERSON> and her partner, <PERSON> Otto </PERSON> <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Frisch </PERSON>, furnished the theoretical basis showing such a splitting could release huge amounts of energy through chain reactions. The experiments took place in the middle of December, with the key test starting Dec. 16, 1938. In the years before his discovery, <PERSON> Hahn </PERSON> had worked closely with <PERSON> Meitner </PERSON>, who had been forced to emigrate in 1938 as the <ORGANIZATION> Nazis </ORGANIZATION> stepped up their attacks on the Jews. `` It was unusual at that time to have a man and woman working together when they were n't married,'' said <PERSON> Jost </PERSON> <PERSON> Lemmerich </PERSON>, chief organizer of the exhibition. When <PERSON> Hahn </PERSON> won the prize, no mention was made of the work by <PERSON> Meitner </PERSON> or <PERSON> Strassmann </PERSON>. <PERSON> Hahn </PERSON> died in 1968 in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. During Thursday's news conference, <PERSON> Lemmerich </PERSON> was asked why the exhibition stops in 1939, without covering the <ORGANIZATION> Nazis </ORGANIZATION>' scientific research in World War II. `` We stopped there because the history is incomplete,'' he responded. `` We did n't have access to the documents.'' But he hinted another exhibition is possible to show the darker sides of <PERSON> Hahn </PERSON>'s discovery. `` Could n't we, say in five years, have another exhibition about <LOCATION> Hiroshima </LOCATION>?'' he asked rhetorically. <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Tagespiegel </ORGANIZATION> newspaper on Nov. 27 said <PERSON> Hahn </PERSON> wrote in his diary of the <LOCATION> Hiroshima </LOCATION> attack that he had a clear conscience `` that neither during the discovery nor later did I want to work for the use of uranium fission as a war weapon.'' At the time, <PERSON> Hahn </PERSON> and other top German atomic scientists were being detained in a British camp, according to the newspaper. <PERSON> Speer </PERSON>, <PERSON> Hitler </PERSON>'s armaments minister and the Third <PERSON> Reich </PERSON>'s top architect, said that in 1942 he had heard of `` a group of scientists who were on the track of a weapon which could annihilate whole cities, perhaps throw the island of <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> out of the fight.'' He continued that two months later he visited with scientists in <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> to be briefed on `` atomic research,'' as the Nazi <PERSON> Reich </PERSON> struggled to find a way to win World War II. `` Along with scientists whose names I no longer recall, the subsequent Nobel Prize winners <PERSON> Otto </PERSON> <PERSON> Hahn </PERSON> and <PERSON> Werner </PERSON> <PERSON> Heisenberg </PERSON> were present,'' <PERSON> Speer </PERSON> wrote in his memoirs, `` Inside the Third Reich.'' <PERSON> Heisenberg </PERSON> told <PERSON> Speer </PERSON> that building such a bomb was possible but it would take at least two years.
