<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The results of the November television rating sweeps period indicates that, among the three networks, <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> took the worst hit from the summer writers' strike. `` The strike really hurt <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION>,'' said <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Poltrack </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> vice president for marketing. `` We did n't have any big events to fill in'' such as <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION>'s 18-hour miniseries `` War and Remembrance.'' He said <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> also had fewer established half-hour sitcoms than the competition. Those shows got back into production quicker than hour dramas. <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> was the only one of the three networks to show a rise in ratings this November compared to last November, when it came in third in the sweeps. Its `` Roseanne'' was the highest-rated new series in November. CBS and <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> tied for second in terms of regular series programming, according to <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION>' analysis of the <ORGANIZATION> A.C. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nielsen </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> numbers. But <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> had a three-point lead on <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> when it came to miniseries and movies. <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION>, with five of the top 10 series and the five top-rated movies, handily won the sweeps, one of four months a year when network affiliates' ratings are measured for purposes of negotiating local advertising rates. <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> had an average, prime-time rating of 15.4. <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> had an average rating of 14.0 and CBS 12.0. Each rating point represents 904,000 households with televisions. `` The Cosby Show'' was the highest-rated network show with a rating of 26.3, down from the 32.3 the show got in November 1987. In fact, all the top-rated series suffered ratings declines. Because of strike-caused production delays on its regular series, <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> rushed to the air with the first part of its more than 30-hour `` War and Remembrance,'' a sequel to `` The Winds of War.'' Except for two two-part movies, `` War and Remembrance'' was the only miniseries of the November sweeps. It ended with a disappointing 18.6 rating and 29 share, but was good enough to save <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> from third place in the sweeps. <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> will run the remainder of the miniseries next May, said spokeswoman <PERSON> Janice </PERSON> <PERSON> Gretemeyer </PERSON>. Sweeps programming brought more viewers to their sets. More households used television, but 3 percent fewer sets were tuned to networks. That was an improvement, though, on the season-to-date 6 percent decline in network viewing. And some of the November decline was attributable to low network viewing on election night. One of the most significant numbers was the increase in viewing of independent stations, which have become more aggressive during sweeps periods. <ORGANIZATION> Fox </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, whose affiliates are counted as independent stations, experienced a dramatic rise in ratings, an average 5.5 compared to 3.7 a year ago. Part of that increase was because <PERSON> Fox </PERSON> was running new episodes of its most popular programs, `` <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s Most Wanted'' and `` Married ... With Children'' during the summer when the networks were in repeats Those shows apparently developed a following that stuck with them in the fall when the networks were struggling to get delayed shows on the air. But independent stations also did well by taking over what was previously a network source of programming _ theatrical release movies. The networks have all but abandoned theatrical movies as a source of ratings, <PERSON> Poltrack </PERSON> said. Meanwhile, independent stations are able to garner competitive ratings by running such films as `` 48 Hours'' and `` The Godfather.'' Pay cable also experienced an increase in viewership during the sweeps. <ORGANIZATION> HBO </ORGANIZATION> was up to an average rating of 8.3, compared to 6.9 a year ago. That was the first increase for <ORGANIZATION> HBO </ORGANIZATION> in the five years since the networks began analyzing pay cable performance during sweeps. <PERSON> Poltrack </PERSON> predicted that January will be `` critical'' for the networks, because it will be their first chance in the strike-delayed season to recoup regular series viewers. `` We look to the future, not to the past,'' he said.
