<HEAD>Police Seeking Criminal Charges In 1985 Jumbo Crash</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TETSUO JIMBO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 After three years investigating the worst single-plane crash in history, police on Thursday sought criminal charges against employees of the aircraft maker, airline and <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transport </ORGANIZATION> Police said the crash that killed 520 people was caused by professional negligence of 20 people, including four <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> employees, <ORGANIZATION> Japan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lines </ORGANIZATION> employees and four from the transport ministry. They were responsible for aircraft repairs, maintenance and inspection. The Seattle-based aircraft manufacturer Thursday rejected the report and denied Japanese charges it hindered the investigation. <ORGANIZATION> Gunma </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Prefectural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Police </ORGANIZATION> handed results of the probe to the <ORGANIZATION> Maebashi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Prosecutor </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION>, which will decide whether to press charges for negligence, a criminal offense in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>. Police said they were unable to question the four <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> employees. But they said documents confiscated from <ORGANIZATION> Japan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lines </ORGANIZATION> provided enough evidence to substantiate their involvement. The four reportedly supervised a faulty repair of the aircraft in 1978 but have refused repeated police requests for interviews. The <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 747 plowed into a mountain during a flight from <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Osaka </LOCATION> on Aug. 12, 1985, killing all but four people aboard. <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> is one of a few countries in which criminal charges are sought against people responsible for airplane accidents, said <PERSON> Hiroshi </PERSON> <PERSON> Itakura </PERSON>, criminal law professor at <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Nihon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. `` The most important thing in an accident like this is to pinpoint the cause of the accident rather than to prosecute individuals,'' said <PERSON> Itakura </PERSON>. `` But unlike the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, under Japanese criminal law corporations can not be charged for wrongdoing.'' <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> Air Lines President <PERSON> Susumu </PERSON> <PERSON> Yamachi </PERSON> said his company is taking the police report seriously. <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION>, however, rejected it. `` <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> does not believe that criminal acts were committed by anyone and hopes that the district prosecutor's office also will conclude that there was no criminal conduct,'' the company said in a statement. Company sources said it planned to respond to the police inquiry, but was unlikely to allow <LOCATION> Japanese </LOCATION> police to question individual employees. <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> has disclosed that it performed faulty repairs on the aircraft after a minor accident in 1978 damaged the rear bulkhead, the metal partition that protects the pressurized cabin. The aircraft skidded on its tail during a rough landing in 1978 at <LOCATION> Osaka </LOCATION> <LOCATION> International </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION> and underwent major repairs, according to <ORGANIZATION> JAL </ORGANIZATION>. A government report in 1987 concluded that improper repairs accelerated metal fatigue, which caused the bulkhead to burst, blowing off part of the plane's tail fin and sending the jumbo jet out of control. Police said the accident could have been avoided if <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> had performed the repairs properly, if <ORGANIZATION> Japan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lines </ORGANIZATION> had checked repairs adequately, and if the transport ministry had inspected the aircraft properly. <ORGANIZATION> JAL </ORGANIZATION> said about 70 percent of compensation claims have been settled. The company and <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> agreed to share compensation for victims' families and the four survivors.
