<TEXT>
 Agriculture Secretary <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lyng </PERSON> on Thursday unveiled the government's 1989 program for rice farmers with a national average price-support level of $ 6.50 for each 100 pounds. That is down from a national average of $ 6.63 in 1988. Price support loans are paid by the government's <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Credit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> to farmers who post their crops as collateral. Because producers are free to forfeit the crops and keep the cash, the system puts a floor under prices. Farmers must meet program requirements to qualify for federal subsidies. <PERSON> Lyng </PERSON> announced a required acreage reduction of 25 percent. This represents land that farmers can not plant and is designed to prevent surpluses. He set the established target price at $ 10.80 for each 100 pounds, down from $ 11.15 this year. Target prices are used in calculating so-called deficiency payments that the government provides as income supports to participants in some programs. Other provisions of the rice program: _ Whole kernel milled rice price support rates were set at $ 10.81 per hundredweight for long grain and $ 9.81 for medium and short grain rice The broken kernel rate for all rice classes is $ 5.41. _ Producers who pledged 1989 crop rice as collateral for price support loans will not be permitted to purchase marketing certificates when repaying loans at the marketing loan repayment rate _ The discretionary inventory reduction program will not be implemented _ Farmers may sign up for the program between Dec. 19 and April 14
