<HEAD>US Embassy Monitoring Conditions in Khmer Rouge Camps</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER ENG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> has changed its policy and now sends staff members to monitor conditions in Cambodian refugee camps run by the communist <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION>, a spokesman for the mission said Thursday. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials had feared previously that an embassy presence in the camps, where human rights violations are widespread, would be used for political propaganda, sources reported. The Embassy said camp visits began in September. American policy still is to avoid substantive contact with the <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION>, which ruled <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> in 1975-78 and killed hundreds of thousands of people. It now is the largest guerrilla army fighting Vietnamese occupation forces. The <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION> controls four U.N.-aided camps in <LOCATION> Thailand </LOCATION> near the Cambodian border housing tens of thousands of refugees. Documented abuses include forced military portering, relocation to dangerous areas, denial of access to medical treatment and at least two executions this year. `` We began these visits solely because of our humanitarian concern for the populations of these camps,'' embassy spokesman <PERSON> Ross </PERSON> <PERSON> Petzing </PERSON> said. `` We have made these visits only when representatives of international organizations are present. Our visits are solely to monitor conditions in the camps and are conducted by officers of the embassy's refugee section.'' <PERSON> Petzing </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> representatives had made about five visits. <PERSON> Shepard </PERSON> <PERSON> Lowman </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Laos </LOCATION> desk until last December, said the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government `` did n't make much of an effort'' before to find out about the camps. `` You did n't think about a return to power of the <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION> because you were dealing with a stalemate,'' he said in an interview Thursday. `` As people became more convinced a settlement is possible ... the <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION> question is very critical. `` It is <LOCATION> Thailand </LOCATION> and Thai sovereignty involved. It's a Thai decision. We should encourage the Thais, though, to increasingly press for greater access to those camps to ensure the people are treated in a humanitarian way. `` I think it is in the Thai national interest to avoid a return to power of the <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION>.'' <PERSON> Lowman </PERSON> is president of a <ORGANIZATION> Refugees </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION>, a voluntary agency based in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. On Nov. 25, the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> condemned forced relocations of civilians from the Ta <PERSON> Luan </PERSON> camp. International relief officials said about 7,000 refugees were moved from Ta <PERSON> Luan </PERSON> to <LOCATION> Khao </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Phlu </LOCATION>, a heavily mined, malarial jungle along the frontier, and thousands of others were moved out of O'Trao. Relief officials said the guerrillas apparently planned to use them to populate areas in <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> from which Vietnamese troops have withdrawn. The new sites have been shelled this month from inside <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION>, forcing 3,000-5 ,000 people back to <LOCATION> Ta </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Luan </LOCATION> A relief official who visited the camp recently said many returned on foot, carrying their belongings in backpacks. `` They were all digging shelters at Ta <PERSON> Luan </PERSON>,'' he said. `` They were afraid Ta <PERSON> Luan </PERSON> also would come under attack.'' On Tuesday, the <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION> radio denied relocating anyone by force and said it had not forced refugees to work as porters. It broadcast an `` open letter from a group of refugees'' in <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION> camps saying they were performing a voluntary patriotic duty to hlp liberate <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION>. People who escaped say all except elderly people and pregnant women were forced to fight or walk through mined forests carrying rice, weapons, ammunition and other supplies to the front lines inside <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION>. Those who refused were jailed in harsh conditions, sometimes in underground prisons with little food and their ankles shackled to posts, they said in recent interviews with visiting reporters.
