official of the private group, which has lobbied in behalf of Soviet Jews since 1971, said OVIR, the Soviet emigration office, had told `` refusenik circles'' in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> that a total of 120 people would have their secrecy restrictions lifted. <PERSON> Shoshana </PERSON> <PERSON> Cardin </PERSON>, chairman of the conference, welcomed `` the lifting of secrecy imposed for many years on former prisoners of conscience and long-term refuseniks. We look forward to the speedy drafting of permission to emigrate to all those whose secrecy has been lifted.'' Also among those notified were <PERSON> Vladimir </PERSON> <PERSON> Kislik </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> physicist who first applied for an exit permit in 1973, and <PERSON> Roald </PERSON> <PERSON> Zelichonok </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Leningrad </LOCATION> electrical engineer who has been trying to leave the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> since 1978. <PERSON> Kislik </PERSON> was arrested in 1981 on charges of malicious hooliganism and served a three-year labor sentence. <PERSON> Zelichonok </PERSON> was arrested in 1985 on charges of defaming the state and served eight months. <PERSON> Strober </PERSON> said he knew of 42 Soviet Jews who had been notified the restriction was being lifted.
