<HEAD>Commerce Reports to Reagan on Restricting Oil Imports</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> on Thursday sent to President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> a secret recommendation on whether oil imports should be restricted. Some domestic energy producers organized as the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> filed a petition with the department a year ago requesting an investigation of whether imported oil threatens national security. The report to the president is the outcome of the investigation. President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> has 90 days to decide what to do, which means he could leave the whole question to President-elect <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>. `` The report is secret until the president makes a decision,'' said department spokeswoman <PERSON> Desiree </PERSON> <PERSON> Tucker </PERSON>. Under provisions of a 1962 law, the president may limit imports of items found to threaten national security. The crude oil price collapse of 1986 devastated <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> producers, who had gone all-out to find new oil following the price increases of the 1970s. From 48 percent of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> consumption in 1977, imported crude and refined products fell to 32 percent of consumption in 1985, but rose to 40 percent for all of last year. For the first 10 months of 1988, imports were 41 percent of consumption compared with 39 percent in the same 1987 period. October's imports were 43 percent vs. 41 percent in October 1987. Several government reports have warned that imports could reach 50 percent in the 1990s. `` At this rate we could hit 50 percent by 1990,'' said <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> McCord </PERSON>, chairman of <ORGANIZATION> Enserch </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>.
