 The commander of the <ORGANIZATION> Marine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION>' <LOCATION> Parris </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> S.C. </LOCATION>, Recruit Depot, rejecting the advice of his legal adviser, granted clemency to a female corporal convicted of homosexual conduct, the corps said Thursday. Maj. Gen. <PERSON> Jarvis </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lynch </PERSON>, in an order signed Wednesday but not released until late Thursday, ordered the one-year prison term handed Cpl. <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Baum </PERSON> reduced to 226 days, said Maj. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> McLean </PERSON>, a spokesman. He also ordered her dishonorable discharge upgraded to a bad conduct discharge, the spokesman said, but left untouched the portions of the sentence that reduced her in rank to private and required forfeiture of all pay and allowances. `` Combined with routine credit for good behavior, this effectively means she will be released from the brig on December 15,'' <PERSON> McLean </PERSON> added. `` I'm obviously extremely happy that Major General <PERSON> Lynch </PERSON> saw fit to reduce her time so that she'll be out for Christmas,'' said <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Barrett </PERSON> <PERSON> Boss </PERSON>, one of <PERSON> Baum </PERSON>'s defense attorneys. `` But this does not change the fact that <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON> <PERSON> Baum </PERSON> has had to spend more than five months in prison as punishment for her sexual preferences,'' <PERSON> Boss </PERSON> added. <PERSON> Lynch </PERSON> had been urged by his staff judge advocate at <LOCATION> Parris </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> to deny a defense bid for clemency, even though <PERSON> Baum </PERSON> claimed to have been promised leniency by a prosecutor in exchange for her cooperation with investigators. The <ORGANIZATION> Marine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION> denied the prosecuting attorney in the case had ever made a binding promise to the enlisted woman in soliciting her cooperation with investigators, but promised <PERSON> Lynch </PERSON> would review all the arguments in the case. <PERSON> Baum </PERSON>, 24, of <LOCATION> Mishawaka </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ind. </LOCATION>, was convicted at court martial last June and sentenced to a year in prison as part of a wide-ranging investigation of alleged lesbian conduct among <LOCATION> Parris </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> instructors. She is serving her sentence in a brig at the <LOCATION> Quantico </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, Marine Base. Last month, in a memorandum dated Nov. 8, the top staff lawyer at <LOCATION> Parris </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> recommended <PERSON> Lynch </PERSON> deny <PERSON> Baum </PERSON> any clemency. Col. <PERSON> Gerald </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON>, the staff judge advocate, noted briefly in his memo that the prosecutor in <PERSON> Baum </PERSON>'s case _ Maj. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Beck </PERSON> _ had recommended a reduction in sentence because of her `` post-trial cooperation'' and because of `` corroboration'' of claims that she had been sexually abused as a child. Nonetheless, <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> recommended the general `` approve the sentence as adjudged.'' The only explanation <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> offered was a single sentence stating: `` No corrective action based upon trial error or the review procedure is appropriate.'' <PERSON> McLean </PERSON> said Thursday he could not elaborate on <PERSON> Lynch </PERSON>'s reasons for granting clemency despite that recommendation. `` The general took this action after reviewing all the facts and concluding that this sentence modification was in the best interest of good order and discipline in the corps and of Corporal Baum,'' <PERSON> McLean </PERSON> said. According to <PERSON> Boss </PERSON>, <PERSON> Baum </PERSON> agreed to