<HEAD>Pier Fire Kills One Man</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MORRO BAY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A swift-moving fire destroyed an oil-soaked pier early Thursday, killing one man and burning at least 11 boats and two cars, authorities said. Authorities ordered a brief evacuation of a nearby area after hearing reports the pier was treated with creosote, a carcinogenic substance. One man asleep in his boat when the fire broke out died when his craft caught fire, said <ORGANIZATION> Morro </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bay </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fire </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> Harpster </PERSON>. The man was not immediately identified. A man and a woman also were taken to <LOCATION> Sierra </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Vista </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hospital </LOCATION> for treatment. Their conditions were not immediately available. Firefighters were able to save shops and restaurants near the pier. The fire was reported at about 6:15 a.m. Firefighters were told by people at the scene that the pier was treated with creosote, a carcinogen the federal <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> has banned from over-the-counter sales as a wood treatment and from use as a pesticide. Authorities ordered an evacuation of businesses and residences downwind from the fire for about a quarter mile. A Coast Guard Marine Safety crew was en route from <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> to check for pollution, said <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>.
