<HEAD>Snow Falls Around Great Lakes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Up to a foot of snow fell Thursday around <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Erie </LOCATION>, with lesser amounts around the rest of the <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lakes </LOCATION>, and parts of <LOCATION> Arkansas </LOCATION> had lowland flooding from recent heavy rain. By the midday, snow fell from central <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> state and the northeast two-thirds of <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> across the lower Great Lakes, northern <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, northern <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION>, northern <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>, southern <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION>. On the downwind side of <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Erie </LOCATION>, in western <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> state, about 12 inches of snow fell at <LOCATION> Colden </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Dunkirk </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Springville </LOCATION>. Seven inches fell at <LOCATION> Glenfield </LOCATION>, with 6 inches at <LOCATION> Gowanda </LOCATION> and 5 at <LOCATION> Silver </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Creek </LOCATION>. Along the southern shore of the lake in <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, about 8 inches of snow covered <PERSON> North </PERSON> <PERSON> Perry </PERSON>, <PERSON> Madison </PERSON> and northern <LOCATION> Geauga </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> by early afternoon. Lesser amounts over northeastern <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> included 4 inches at Mentor, <LOCATION> Ashtabula </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON>, 2 inches at <LOCATION> Chardon </LOCATION> and an inch at <LOCATION> Burton </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Traverse </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mich. </LOCATION>, got 3 inches of snow in the six hours up to 1 p.m. EST. Elsewhere, snow was scattered across central <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION> into central <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION>. In eastern and northeastern <LOCATION> Arkansas </LOCATION>, low