<FIRST>u w AM-NursingHomes 1stLd-Writethru a0753 12-01 0783</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nursing Homes, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0753,770</SECOND>
<HEAD>With AM-Nusing Homes List</HEAD>
<HEAD>Nursing Homes Rated in Consumer Guide</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after pvs 7th graf bgng ``Dr. Paul ...'' to
include comment from AARP</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JERRY ESTILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The most recent surprise inspections of the nation's nursing homes showed that 43 percent failed to meet food sanitation standards and nearly 30 percent did n't properly administer drugs or ensure good personal hygiene, the government reported Thursday. In a 75-volume guide for consumers, federal officials released grades for each of the 15,000 nursing homes on 32 of the approximately 500 standards by which they are measured at least once a year in on-site inspections. Overall, the failure rate exceeded 15 percent in 10 categories. But about 2,400 nursing homes received passing marks in all 32 categories. The massive report, a compilation of material previously available only on a piece-meal basis through state regulatory agencies, amounts to the first federally sanctioned catalog for people looking for a nursing home. `` I think this is a landmark achievement, not because it an end to itself but because it will help people pose thoughtful, further questions in seeking out a nursing home,'' said Dr. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Roper </PERSON>, head of the <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Care </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Financing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> that oversees <ORGANIZATION> Medicare </ORGANIZATION> and Medicaid. But neither the nursing-home industry nor its severest critics greeted the report with enthusiasm. <PERSON> Elma </PERSON> <PERSON> Holder </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Citizens </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ' </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coalition </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nursing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Home </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reform </ORGANIZATION>, said <PERSON> Roper </PERSON> `` should be embarrassed and ashamed to present these documents so proudly ... At best they provide a teaser to the consumers to try to obtain a copy of the full survey report of the facility.'' Dr. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Willging </PERSON>, executive vice president of the 9,000-memember <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Care </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, the major nursing home trade group, called the report unreliable and `` In fact, the guide could be harmful to consumers who use it as a shortcut to selecting a nursing home.'' But the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Retired </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Persons </ORGANIZATION> praised the report as a `` good start'' toward full disclosure of information about nursing home quality. `` We are pleased that the federal government has taken valuable information about the quality of nursing home care out of its computers and made it available to the individuals and families who need it most,'' said <ORGANIZATION> AARP </ORGANIZATION> Executive Director <PERSON> Horace </PERSON> <PERSON> Deets </PERSON>. <PERSON> Roper </PERSON> acknowledged it should not be viewed as a one-stop guide, and conceded that a major shortcoming was that the 32 performance indicators were listed only as having been `` met'' or `` unmet,'' rather than showing the severity of failures. For example, a nursing home that needed 30 nurses on staff to meet patient-nurse ratios and had only 26 would receive the same `` unmet'' citation as if it only had 10 nurses. By law, the most recent and full report has to be available for inspection at each nursing home, giving more detail for what led to `` unmet'' citations. `` This document ... is not the ultimate report on nursing homes across the country but we present national statistics in order to be helpful in interpreting how a given nursing home compares to other nursing homes across the country,'' <PERSON> Roper </PERSON> said at a news conference. In addition to showing that 42.8 percent of the nursing homes received an `` unmet'' grade when measured against minimum federal standards for food storage, preparation and distribution, the report found these other `` unmet'' percentages: _ Daily personal hygiene standard for patients, 29.8 percent _ Proper and timely administration of prescribed drugs, 29 percent _ Isolation techniques to prevent spread of infection, 24.7 percent _ Rehabilitative care to promote maximum physicial functioning to prevent loss of ability to walk and otherwise move freely, 21.6 percent None of the other 27 categories registered an `` unmet'' percentage above 20 percent. At the A-plus end of the scale, the report shows that 99.7 percent meet requirements for discharging or transferring patients; 99.6 percent allow residents to communicate freely with others; 99.5 percent provide emergency medical services as necessary. <PERSON> Willging </PERSON>, speaking for the industry, noted the report is based on the judgments of more than 3,000 inspectors, and that the most recent inspections included in the document occurred last summer. Some are 18 months old. `` Consumers must not consider the <ORGANIZATION> HCFA </ORGANIZATION> report a substitute for visiting nursing homes during the slection process,'' said <PERSON> Willging </PERSON>. `` Visting and asking the right questions are essential.'' <PERSON> Sheldon </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Goldbert </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Homes </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> For </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aging </ORGANIZATION>, another trade group, said, `` The report renders high-quality care and substandard care nearly indistinguishable by its failure to separate serious, ongoing problems from minor, one-time infractions.'' But Ms. Holder of the non-profit reform coalition said: `` We think the national statistics are misleading. Conditions are worse.''
</TEXT>
