<HEAD>Sixty-Nine Senators Applaud Decision To Bar Arafat From U.S.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Sixty-one senators and eight senators-elect, including Vice President-elect <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>, on Thursday endorsed the decision by Secretary of State <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> to deny a visa to <LOCATION> Palestinian </LOCATION> leader <PERSON> Yasser </PERSON> <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON>. The 35 Republicans and 34 Democrats told <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> in a letter that <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON> was associated with terrorism and has `` no place in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>.'' Barring <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON> was entirely justified because <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON> is chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Palestine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION>, which, they said, `` engages in terrorism.'' `` The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government has convincing evidence that <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> elements have engaged in terrorism against Americans,'' the lawmakers told <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON>. `` As you rightfully and lawfully concluded, such an individual has no place in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>.'' The letter-writing effort was organized by <PERSON> Sens </PERSON>. <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> <PERSON> DeConcini </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Ariz </LOCATION>., and <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Grassley </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Iowa </LOCATION> `` We must continue our policy of denying admission to our country those, including <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON>, who profess terrorism as a tool of foreign policy,'' <PERSON> DeConcini </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Grassley </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> under <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON> remains committed to terrorism and added: `` <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON>'s action makes it clear that the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> will not tolerate such activity.'' <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON> sought a visa to