<HEAD>Man Who Claimed He Taped Brawley Advisers Is Indicted For Perjury</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A man who said he recorded conversations of advisers to <PERSON> Tawana </PERSON> <PERSON> Brawley </PERSON> _ who said she was a victim of a racist sex attack but refused to cooperate with police _ but then produced only blank tapes has been indicted. <PERSON> Samuel </PERSON> <PERSON> McClease </PERSON>, 26, a self-described surveillance expert from <LOCATION> Newark </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>, was indicted by a federal grand jury Wednesday on charges of perjury and obstruction of justice. The indictment closely paralleled a criminal complaint filed against him last summer. The action comes a month after a state grand jury concluded that Ms. <PERSON> Brawley </PERSON>, a black teen-ager from upstate <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, had concocted her story of abduction and sexual assault by whites. <PERSON> McClease </PERSON>, who has been free on $ 100,000 bond, will be arraigned Dec. 8, said <PERSON> Deborah </PERSON> <PERSON> Corley </PERSON>, a spokeswoman for <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> Rudolph </PERSON> <PERSON> Giuliani </PERSON>. He faces a maximum penalty of five years in prison and a $ 250,000 fine on each count, if convicted. There was no telephone listing for McClease in <LOCATION> Newark </LOCATION>. His lawyer, <PERSON> Leonard </PERSON> <PERSON> Joy </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Legal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aid </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION>, was not in his <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION> office when called for comment. Ms. <PERSON> Brawley </PERSON>, formerly of <ORGANIZATION> Wappingers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Falls </ORGANIZATION>, touched off a nationwide controversy after claiming she had been abducted and sexually assaulted for several days by up to six white men, including one who flashed a police badge. Ms. <PERSON> Brawley </PERSON> and her family, however, refused to cooperate with state investigators on the advice of lawyers <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Vernon </PERSON> <PERSON> Mason </PERSON> and <PERSON> Alton </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Maddox </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> and the Rev. <PERSON> Al </PERSON> <PERSON> Sharpton </PERSON>. In June, <PERSON> McClease </PERSON> told federal investigators and television reporters that he had bugged the conversations of Ms. <PERSON> Brawley </PERSON>'s advisers and could produce tapes that undermined her story <PERSON> McClease </PERSON> claimed <PERSON> Sharpton </PERSON> hired him to bug his home as well as <PERSON> Mason </PERSON>'s home and office. <PERSON> Sharpton </PERSON> has vigorously denied McClease's claims. According to the indictment, <PERSON> McClease </PERSON> claimed he had 10 audio tapes of conversations among <PERSON> Mason </PERSON>, <PERSON> Maddox </PERSON> and <PERSON> Sharpton </PERSON>. But <PERSON> McClease </PERSON> could produce only blank tapes in reply to a grand jury subpoena. He signed an affidavit saying he could not produce the tapes.
