will require crew members to call out items that have been cleared on a checklist. Earlier this week at the <ORGANIZATION> NTSB </ORGANIZATION> hearing, Flight 1141 Capt. <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Davis </PERSON> testified he had used hand gestures to signal his progress through the checklist. <PERSON> Ken </PERSON> <PERSON> Adams </PERSON>, a flight instructor, told the panel Thursday that one major change on crew members' flight checklists will be to look at the wing flaps twice. `` We started deploying them -LRB- the flaps -RRB- as soon as we go so the public can see them and say they're down,'' he said. The wing flaps have been the focus of much of the panel's investigation Investigators have been puzzled that the plane's flap handle was found up, the retracted position, although some of the plane's flaps and slats were extended. A switch for a system that would have warned the pilots of <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lines </ORGANIZATION> Flight 1141 that the jet's wing flaps were improperly set for takeoff had corroded, a veteran engineer told federal investigators Thursday. <ORGANIZATION> NTSB </ORGANIZATION> officials say the hearing is only for fact-gathering and that no conclusions will be released until a report is made public in six months. All three crew members agreed before the board that, to the best of their recollection, they made all necessary preflight preparations, including setting the flaps, although they may have bent several <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION> regulations. One of their admitted technical violations was allowing a flight attendant into the cockpit during a long delay before takeoff.
