<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Chinese Foreign Minister <PERSON> Qian </PERSON> <PERSON> Qichen </PERSON> arrived Thursday as his nation's first high-level envoy to the Soviet capital in 31 years. He will be meeting Soviet officials to seek agreement on the conflict in <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> and prepare for a 1989 summit. The summit would be the first since 1959 when <PERSON> Nikita </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Khrushchev </PERSON> met Chinese leader <PERSON> Mao </PERSON> <PERSON> Tse-Tung </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Qian </PERSON>'s visit is the first by a <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> foreign minister since the visit of <PERSON> Chou </PERSON> <PERSON> En-lai </PERSON> in 1957. Soviet Foreign Minister <PERSON> Eduard </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON> greeted him at <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Sheremetyevo </ORGANIZATION> 2 Airport. They are to conduct two days of talks, and the Chinese official said he also expected to meet with Soviet President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>. `` <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, as two great neighboring countries, must live in peace and neighborly relations,'' <PERSON> Qian </PERSON> said in an arrival statement distributed by the Soviet news agency <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION>. `` We are glad that in recent years Chinese-Soviet relations gradually are improving,'' he was quoted as saying. Relations between the two communist powers soured in the early 1960s in a struggle over the direction of world communism. They reached a low point in 1969, when each side sent at least 1 million soldiers to the border and fought a short frontier war. However, <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> has made several recent overtures to <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, ordering a pullout of Soviet troops from <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>, reducing Soviet troops on the Chin