<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Police tore down barricades of burning tires, fired tear gas and arrested hundreds of protesters Thursday during an illegal general strike against government austerity measures, officials said. Police reported arresting 265 people during the daylong strike that the government had banned. Strike leader <PERSON> Valentin </PERSON> <PERSON> Pacho </PERSON> claimed police arrested more than 500 people, most of them when demonstrators tried to march from surrounding neighborhoods into downtown <LOCATION> Lima </LOCATION>. Authorities said leftist guerrillas seized and burned a city bus. However, no injuries were reported during the strike. It was the fourth general work stoppage this year and the fifth against the 3-year-old government of President <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Garcia </PERSON>. The strike comes during growing unrest caused by <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION>'s most serious economic recession this century. Prime Minister <PERSON> Armando </PERSON> <PERSON> Villanueva </PERSON> charged the strike was being manipulated by the Maoist guerrilla movement Shining Path to destabilize and eventually topple the elected government. Labor leaders denied that. At one point, a column of 50 hooded Shining Path guerrillas marched rapidly across a downtown plaza filled with strikers and then dispersed in the crowds. Police exploded tear gas canisters and fired their guns into the air to scatter the protesters. <PERSON> Pacho </PERSON> said 80 percent of unionized workers had joined the strike, but the <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> claimed 90 percent of <LOCATION> Lima </LOCATION>'s offices, factories and other businesses were functioning. The capital is still reeling from a five-day power outage caused by leftist guerrillas last week, as well as sporadic water shortages and growing shortages of basic foods. The country has also been hit with a paralyzing mining strike, that began Oct. 17 and has led to numerous clashes betwe