<HEAD>Malaria, Once under Control, Again Serious in Madagascar</HEAD>
<BYLINE>BY ROBERT WELLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ANTANANARIVO, Madagascar (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 In the central highlands of this island nation, health officials are using <ORGANIZATION> DTT </ORGANIZATION>, banned in other parts of the world, to combat a disease that once was under control _ malaria. Specially trained teams are spraying the inner walls of thousands of homes with the powerful insecticide because it is deemed the most effective and practical way for <LOCATION> Madagascar </LOCATION>, a nation struggling with economic problems. A resurgence of malaria in the central highlands has already claimed thousands of lives in the last two years, and a government report said malaria could claim 100,000 to 250,000 lives in the next six months if emergency measures were not taken. Malaria had largely disappeared from the central highlands, a strip up to 170 miles wide running nearly 850 miles north to south, after <LOCATION> French </LOCATION> colonial authorities used DDT in antimalarial campaigns and drugs to treat those who got the disease. But the spraying stopped after independence in 1960, and in the economic decline that followed a Socialist revolution in 1975, antimalarial drugs, which had to be imported, were not available. At the same time, the highlanders lost the moderate immunity people of hyperendemic malarious areas usually develop. `` When it started coming back, people did n't know what it was,'' said Dr. <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Rakotojoelinadrasana </PERSON>, who directs two <ORGANIZATION> Lutheran </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> clinics. `` They thought it was a new disease and they named it ` Bemangovitra,' which means the ` big chills'.'' Even if people had recognized it as the old <LOCATION> Tazomoka </LOCATION> -LRB- mosquito fever -RRB- there were virtually no drugs available to combat it. The country had no foreign exchange to import drugs, and people would n't have been able to afford to buy them in a country where income has been falling for 20 years and wages average the equivalent of a dollar a day or less `` The nutritional status had fallen so much it made it much more severe than in a healthy population,'' said <PERSON> Edmond </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Gaiffier </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION>. No reliable figures are available on how many people have died of malaria in recent years, as any fever is usually diagnosed as malaria. Few facilities are available for blood tests, and many people have no access to any health care. Health Minister <PERSON> Jean-Jacques </PERSON> <PERSON> Seraphin </PERSON> and the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> representative, Dr. <PERSON> Cyprian </PERSON> <PERSON> Hakizimana </PERSON>, said published reports of 100,000 deaths were exaggerated. World Bank specialists said the toll was probably more in the range of 30,000 and Dr. <PERSON> Pierre </PERSON> <PERSON> Coulanges </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> Pasteur </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> here, said the toll could be as high as 50,000 and in some villages 20 percent of the residents had died. The plan to combat the malaria threat includes two controversial elements. The first is the use of DDT, banned in developed countries after it was found to be entering the food chain. <PERSON> Hakizimana </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> had approved DDT as a one-time measure because of the grave threat <LOCATION> Madagascar </LOCATION> faced, and it will only be used inside houses, not on crops. <PERSON> De </PERSON> <PERSON> Gaiffier </PERSON> said DDT has acquired such a bad name that it was n't easy to find the 50 to 80 tons needed in <LOCATION> Madagascar </LOCATION> It is preferred because it remains effective for six months or more, through the rainy season on the 226,658-square-mile island of 11 million people. Spraying on the walls will be effective because the malarial mosquitoes rest on walls after biting their victims, said <PERSON> Rakotojoelinadrasana </PERSON>. The second controversy involves the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION>'s policy of providing drugs for treatment after people are infected rather than distributing them for prophylaxsis, or prevention Health Minister <PERSON> Seraphin </PERSON> said the government will make drugs available for prophylaxsis only for children up to age 6 and pregnant women. The <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> recommends against use of drugs for prophylaxsis in hyperendemic areas because of the cost, fears that it will facilitate the spread of resistance and concerns about the side effects. `` The WHO recommendation is logical on theoretical grounds,'' <PERSON> Rakotojoelinadrasana </PERSON> said. `` But the problem is that people who get malaria may die from it. As medical doctors we are hesitating to advise people to get malaria and then come to us.'' <PERSON> De </PERSON> <PERSON> Gaiffier </PERSON> said scientists are very worried about the increasing prevalance of malaria in higher elevations. It is `` following economic development up the mountain where there are new population reservoirs with no immunity,'' he added. Farmers are using every piece of land they can find, including steep hillsides, to grow rice and other crops. Rice is heavily consumed in <LOCATION> Madagascar </LOCATION> and rice fields are perfect breeding grounds for malaria mosquitoes.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Thurs PMs Dec. 8</NOTE>
