<HEAD>San Diego Utility Accepts SoCal Edison's $2.5 Billion Buyout Bid</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK EVJE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The parent of <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Edison </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> entered `` the crown jewel of service territories'' when <ORGANIZATION> San </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Diego </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> accepted its $ 2.5 billion buyout bid, utility officials said. The stock-swap deal approved Wednesday by <ORGANIZATION> SDG </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; E directors creates the nation's biggest public utility, and will result in lower electricity rates for customers and higher dividends for shareholders, <ORGANIZATION> Edison </ORGANIZATION> chairman and chief executive <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> said. `` We have concluded that there will be savings passed on to customers, and that this combined institution will be stronger and better able to serve customer needs,'' said <PERSON> Allen </PERSON>, also chief executive of <PERSON> Edison </PERSON>'s unregulated parent, <ORGANIZATION> SCEcorp </ORGANIZATION>, which serves most of <LOCATION> Southern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>. `` We would n't be going into this if we did n't think we could produce better consumer value than each -LRB- utility -RRB- could on its own.'' Customers of the surviving utility also will benefit from its increased financial strength through greater market competitiveness and more efficient energy transmission, <ORGANIZATION> SDG </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; E chairman and chief executive <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Page </PERSON> said. <ORGANIZATION> SCEcorp </ORGANIZATION> also has pledged to file a request for a 10 percent rate reduction