<HEAD>Dollar Lower, Gold Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The dollar fell in early European trading today as the market waited for Friday's release of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> unemployment figures for November, foreign currency dealers said. Gold prices rose. November's unemployment rate is expected to remain at about 5.3 percent. `` If it's a slightly better number, the dollar may rise a bit,'' said a dealer at a large <LOCATION> Frankfurt </LOCATION> bank. But a dealer in <LOCATION> Milan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>, said worse-than-expected figures would hurt the dollar and would indicate that the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> economy is overheating and that the threat of inflation was strong. Dealers said the dollar's weakness is partly due to the strength of the British pound. One pound cost $ 1.8542 in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> at midmorning, more expensive for buyers than late Wednesday's $ 1.8480. `` The -LRB- British -RRB- government's high-interest-rate policy is clear,'' the <LOCATION> Frankfurt </LOCATION> dealer said. `` Demand for the pound is there.'' In <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, where trading ends before <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'s business day begins, the dollar fell 0.28 yen to a closing 121.57. Later, in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, it was quoted at 121.65 yen. Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Wednesday's rates, included: 1.7318 West German marks, down from 1.7375; 1.4513 Swiss francs, down from 1.4548; 5.9135 French francs, down from 5.9327; 1.9552 Dutch guilders, down from 1.9590; 1,278.65 Italian lire, down from 1,284.97; 1.1857 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1872 Gold prices rose on the heels of higher platinum prices, bullion dealers said. Gold opened in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> at a bid price of $ 424.50 a troy ounce, up from $ 423.25 bid late Wednesday. At midmorning, the city's five major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $ 425.50. In <LOCATION> Zurich </LOCATION>, the bid price was $ 425.00, up from $ 422.30 bid late Wednesday. Earlier, in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>, gold spurted ahead $ 2.90 to close at a bid $ 425.52. Silver was quoted in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> at a bid price of $ 6.18 a troy ounce, up from Wednesday's $ 6.14.
