<HEAD>Dollar, Stocks Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The dollar and stock prices closed lower in cautious trading in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> today as participants awaited the release of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> unemployment figures, traders said. The dollar opened lower at 121.28 yen, then rose slightly during the day. It finished trading at 121.57 yen, down 0.28 yen from Wednesday's closing, after ranging between 121.28 and 121.60 yen. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> currency's decline in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> followed an overnight drop in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, where the <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> England </ORGANIZATION> sold dollars in an attempt to keep the British pound from rising against the West German mark, dealers said. Many market players in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> remained on the sidelines ahead of the release of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> jobless rate for November, scheduled for Friday, dealers said. The dollar rose in the afternoon after some trading companies bought the currency, but was not affected strongly, a trader with <ORGANIZATION> Mitsui </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> said. `` Dollar-yen trading is likely to remain inactive in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> until at least Monday,'' she said, speaking on condition of anonymity. Monday is the first day that <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> traders will be able to respond to the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> jobless rate. On the <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, the 225-issue <ORGANIZATION> Nikkei </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Average </ORGANIZATION> fell back 37.44 points or 0.13 percent to 29,541.46. The index gained 94.26 points during the morning to end the early session at a record-high 29,673.16, but reversed direction in the afternoon. On Wednesday, the <ORGANIZATION> Nikkei </ORGANIZATION> index closed at a record high of 29,578.90 after gaining 260.60 points. `` Share prices began to fall as market players became increasingly cautious and directionless before the release of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> jobless rate,'' said an analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Nomura </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION>, speaking on condition of anonymity. He said the most immediate concern of investors was whether the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> would raise interest rates. `` Today's directionless market was easily influenced whenever participants spread rumors, including one that <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> interest rates were likely to rise,'' he added. Volume on the market's first section was an estimated 1.5 billion shares.
