<FIRST>r f PM-DeficitTestimony     12-01 0452</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Deficit Testimony,0475</SECOND>
<HEAD>With PM-Deficit Commission</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Here are excerpts from testimony Wednesday before the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, a bipartisan panel created by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to seek a solution to the nation's deficit problem:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>

</TEXT>
<HEAD>`There Can Be No Dodging the Facts'</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> PAUL </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> VOLCKER </PERSON>, former chairman of the Federal Reserve:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 `` We have enjoyed _ are still enjoying _ an unprecedented period of economic expansion in peacetime. At the same time, there can be no dodging the facts of anemic savings, extraordinarily high current consumption, rapidly growing indebtedness internally and externally, slack growth in productivity, a depreciating currency and renewed inflation. `` Taken together, those factors undermine prospects for longterm growth and aggravate more immediate economic risks, but they also undercut public and congressional support for sustaining our military strength, maintaining open markets and free flows of international investment, and for efforts to encourage development of much poorer nations.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>`The Public Is Ahead of the Politicians'</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 HOUSE SPEAKER <PERSON> JIM </PERSON> <PERSON> WRIGHT </PERSON>: `` If the problem is formidable, so are our resources. Polls also show that the people are willing to pay as we go. They prefer to pay as we go. In some ways the public is ahead of the politicians. In tiptoeing around the problem, inventing creative euphemisms and pretending to believe in pretty illusions, some office-seekers are selling the people short.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>`Our Defense Plans Do Not Reflect What Is Affordable'</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> CHARLES </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> BOWSHER </PERSON>, comptroller general of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, head of the General Accounting Office:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 `` Another example of failing to reflect costs is the defense budget. The most recent Five Year Defense Plan includes programs that will cost at least $ 200 billion more than the funds that are likely to be available. On top of that are the cost overruns that we see looming on the horizon. The simple fact is that our defense plans do not yet reflect the limits on what is affordable. `` Closely related to this is the problem of our aging nuclear weapons complex. We estimate that it will cost $ 100 billion to $ 130 billion over a number of years to clean up and modernize these environmentally hazardous plants.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>`Tax Finance Is Prefereable to Deficit Finance'</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 JOHN A. YOUNG, president of the <ORGANIZATION> Hewlett-Packard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> and chairman of the Council on Competitiveness:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 `` If a formula for substantial deficit-reduction on the spending side alone remains as elusive to the administration, <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> as it has to us, then we expect all parties will consider revenue increases. `` As a group concerned about capital formation and private sector investment, we agree that it is important to pay for federal spending through revenues rather than borrowing. Simply stated, tax finance is preferable to deficit finance.''
</TEXT>
