<HEAD>MIT Moves To Commercialize New Superconductors</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN COOPERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Massachusetts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Technology </ORGANIZATION> has won an early heat in a race to commercialize new superconductors that many scientists believe will eventually be used to probe the brain, detect submarines and help find oil. But researchers at other university and corporate laboratories said Wednesday the race, which could bring huge financial gains to the winner, is far from over. <ORGANIZATION> MIT </ORGANIZATION> received a `` notice of allowability'' from the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Patent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> last week for the first major <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> patent in the field of high-temperature superconductors, materials that conduct electricity with virtually no resistance. MIT officials said the notice is a strong signal that the institute will receive a patent within a few months for a process developed by two professors, <PERSON> Gregory </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Yurek </PERSON> and <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Vander </PERSON> <PERSON> Sande </PERSON>, to make ceramic superconductors more flexible by mixing them with metals like gold or silver. Researchers around the world have been competing to develop and apply ceramic superconductors since they were discovered in January 1986 by two scientists at an <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Machines </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> laboratory in <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> scientists, <PERSON> Georg </PERSON> <PERSON> Bednorz </PERSON> and <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> <PERSON> Mueller </PERSON>, won the 1987 Nobel Prize in physics for their discovery that certain ceramics become superconductive when cooled with liquid nitrogen to about 300 degrees below zero Fahrenheit. Previous superconductors had operated only at minus 418 degrees or below, requiring cooling in liquid helium, which is more costly and difficult to maintain than liquid nitrogen. One problem with the ceramics is that they are brittle. <ORGANIZATION> MIT </ORGANIZATION> says its process greatly increases flexibility, allowing the materials to be made into wire and wound into coils for small motors. Several other applications for patents related to ceramic superconductors are pending, but none have been granted, said <PERSON> Oscar </PERSON> <PERSON> Maston </PERSON>, a spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> Patent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Arlington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Labs </ORGANIZATION> and other companies and universities are working on processes similar to <ORGANIZATION> MIT </ORGANIZATION>'s, said <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Fleury </PERSON>, director of physical research at <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Labs </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Murray </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION> `` The <ORGANIZATION> MIT </ORGANIZATION> technique is significant in that it's one of the earliest,'' <PERSON> Fleury </PERSON> said, `` but it's still too early to tell which, if any, of these processes is going to result in a commercial application. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gallagher </PERSON>, manager of exploratory cryogenics at <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION>'s research center in <LOCATION> Yorktown </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Heights </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, said researchers can easily foresee using the new superconductors in devices to measure brainwaves, locate submarines deep under the sea, detect oil reserves and process radar signals But those uses are probably at least five years away, <PERSON> Gallagher </PERSON> said, and many problems with superconductors will have to be solved first. Among them, he said, are limits to the amount of current the new materials can carry. <ORGANIZATION> MIT </ORGANIZATION> said it has licensed exclusive rights to its patent to a company founded last year by four of the institute's faculty members. <ORGANIZATION> MIT </ORGANIZATION> officials refused to disclose the terms of the licensing agreement with the company, <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Superconductor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Cambridge </LOCATION>.
