<FIRST>r f BC-China-FuturesMarket     12-01 0336</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-China-Futures Market,0348</SECOND>
<HEAD>China Delays Opening of First Futures Market</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> will delay for a year the opening of the socialist world's first futures market, an official daily said Thursday. The <ORGANIZATION> China </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Daily </ORGANIZATION> said a futures market will be launched on a trial basis in central <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Henan </LOCATION> province by the end of next year. In May, plans were announced to open a market in the southern city of <LOCATION> Canton </LOCATION> by the end of 1988, but the daily said an investigative group under the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s cabinet, decided to put off the starting date. <PERSON> Chang </PERSON> <PERSON> Qing </PERSON>, senior researcher in the group, said <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> wanted more time to learn from experts in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> and become better prepared. A futures market, formerly regarded in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> as a form of capitalist speculation, allows traders and producers of raw materials to negotiate a set price for what they think a commodity will be worth at a future date. The producer is guaranteed that price regardless of subsequent fluctuations in the market. The need for futures markets has arisen with the decontrol of prices for many commodities that has resulted in sharp price fluctuations. Produce markets in particular have been plagued by gluts and shortages caused by farmers' inability to forecast the market. The daily said the market in <LOCATION> Henan </LOCATION>, a major agriculture center, will deal in wheat and other grains. About 150 people, mostly from <LOCATION> Henan </LOCATION>, recently gathered in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> for a 10-day training course in futures markets, it said. The <LOCATION> Henan </LOCATION> market will only open prices to trading twice a week because of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s backward telecommunications system, it said. If it is a success, markets will be opened in <LOCATION> Jilin </LOCATION> in the northeast for corn, <LOCATION> Sichuan </LOCATION> in the west for pigs and <LOCATION> Guangdong </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Hebei </LOCATION> in the south and north for raw materials. It said the investigative group is studying whether foreign businessmen will be allowed to participate in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s futures markets. Initially, only Chinese will be able to take part, it said.
