<FIRST>u f PM-LeadingIndicators 3rdLd-Writethru f0024 12-01 0685</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Leading Indicators, 3rd Ld-Writethru, f0024,0702</SECOND>
<HEAD>Leading Index Up Slightly In October</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: Subs 17th graf, The leading, to reflect revisions for earlier
months</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The government said today its chief forecasting gauge of future economic activity edged up a sluggish 0.1 percent in October after falling a month earlier. The <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s Index of Leading Indicators had previously been estimated as falling only 0.1 percent in September, but today's report revised that downturn to minus 0.3 percent. Economists said the movement of the index appears to be pointing to slower growth, but they have been hard-pressed to find much sign of it yet. Other statistics for October, the latest available, all look very strong. Unemployment is at a 14-year low, factories are using more of their capacity than at any time in 8 -LCB- years and personal income posted its steepest increase in a year. `` The message is clear that the fourth quarter is starting out very well. ... There are no particular imbalances ... -LRB- and -RRB- that suggests the economy should keep on expanding nicely for another six to nine months,'' said <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> <PERSON> Sinai </PERSON>, an economist for <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co </ORGANIZATION>. However, the leading index is `` clearly signaling a slowdown'' in the second half of next year, he said in advance of today's report. Over the last 12 months, it's risen only 0.5 percent, compared with a gain of 6.0 percent for the previous 12-month period. It was the smallest October-to-October increase since 1979-80, beore the last recession. In October, four of nine available indicators were pointing to faster growth, while five were pointing to slower growth. The factors pushing the index up, in order of magnitude, were an increase in building permits, a rise in stock prices, a jump in new orders to manufacturers for consumer goods and a drop in initial claims for state unemployment insurance. The negative factors, ordered from largest to smallest, were faster deliveries to companies, a sign of slackening demand; a drop in the price of industrial materials; a decline in the inflation-adjusted money supply; a shortening in the length of the average workweek, and a fall in orders for business equipment. The various changes left the index at 193.0 percent of its 1967 base of 100. <PERSON> Samuel </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kahan </PERSON>, an economist with <ORGANIZATION> Kleinwort </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Benson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Government </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, said the index's prediction of slower growth is not necessarily false. Some sort of moderation, given the current bouyancy, is not unlikely in the last half of 1989, he said. `` However, I would not leap to the conclusion that a recession is coming,'' he said. Given current economic conditions, a significant slowdown or recession wo n't occur until the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> pushes interest rates sharply higher, he said. The <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION>, fearing that too-strong demand will push prices higher, has been trying to slow expansion of the gross national product, the broadest measure of the economy's health, to a non-inflationary 2 percent to 2.5 percent. The GNP grew at a moderate 2.6 percent annual pace in the third quarter, down from a 3.2 percent pace in the first half of 1988. However, most analysts were expecting it to pick up again in the first three months of next year when the negative effects from the summer drought are no longer acting as a drag. That would put the economy well into the middle of its seventh year of expansion, a peacetime record. The leading index, before falling in September, rose 0.5 percent in August and fell 0.8 percent in July. It rose 1.6 percent in June and dropped 0.7 percent in May. Economists caution against drawing immediate conclusions from the index even though since its creation in 1948 it has correctly predicted all eight recessions by dropping three times in a row. However, it has also falsely predicted a recession four times. Preliminary estimates of the index are often revised substantially in later months. For instance, declines were initially reported for five consecutive months _ from September 1987 through January _ but later revisions wiped out all but two of the drops.
</TEXT>
