<FIRST>u f PM-EconomyRdp 2ndLd-Writethru f0029 12-01 0665</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Economy Rdp, 2nd Ld-Writethru, f0029,0684</SECOND>
<HEAD>Leading Index Up Slightly In October</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 4 grafs to update with construction spending
report; picks up 2nd graf pvs, ``The Commerce...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Construction spending rose 0.9 percent, its heftiest increase in three months, with widespread gains reported in housing, government and commercial building, the government reported today. In a separate report, the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said its chief forecasting gauge of future economic activity rose a tiny 0.1 percent in October after falling a month earlier. Building activity rose to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of $ 409.2 billion in October following a 0.7 percent increase in September and a 0.2 percent rise in August. It was the best showing since a 1.5 percent jump in July. But despite the recent increases, construction activity has been modest this year, advancing 2.1 percent in the past 12 months. Taking a 1.7 percent rise in construction costs into account, activity increased only 0.4 percent over the past 12 months. The <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s Index of Leading Indicators had previously been estimated as falling only 0.1 percent in September, but today's report revised that downturn to minus 0.3 percent. The leading index, before edging down in September, rose 0.5 percent in August and fell 0.7 percent in July after dropping in May. Economists said the movement of the index appears to be pointing to slower growth, but they have been hard-pressed to find much sign of it lately. Other statistics for October, the latest available, have been strong, including one showing unemployment at a 14-year low. On Wednesday, the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> reported that personal income increased 1.8 percent, the biggest rise since October 1987, to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of $ 4.18 trillion last month. The gain followed modest increases of 0.5 percent in September and 0.4 percent in August. The numbers raised some concerns about inflation, but a separate report to the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> indicated the economy was slowing down. In a review of the economy based on assessments from the 12 regional <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> banks, the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> reported `` an apparently slower pace'' of growth, moderate wage increases and slightly eased price pressures in several manufacturing industries. Financial markets rallied, interpreting the report as a signal that <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> members were less worried about inflation than previously thought, and therefore less likely to boost interest rates. The Dow Jones average of 30 industrial stocks rose 12.98 to 2,114.51, giving the well-known barometer a gain of nearly 40 points over the past three sessions. The government attributed about half of last month's increase in income to farm subsidy payments and bonuses to auto workers. However, excluding those factors, income still would have risen a hefty 0.9 percent. `` This throws cold water on the view the economy slowed down much,'' said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Hagens </PERSON>, an economist with <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wefa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION>, a <PERSON> Bala </PERSON> <PERSON> Cynwyd </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Pa. </LOCATION>, forecasting firm. `` It may have taken a bit of a pause in August and September, but it came roaring back in October.'' The concern in financial markets has been that growth is too strong. High levels of employment will lead to higher wages, and strong consumer demand will lead to higher prices, they fear. Personal consumption spending, which includes everything except interest payments on debt, was up a robust 0.8 percent to an annual rate of $ 3.30 trillion following a weak 0.1 percent rise in September. The biggest spending increase last month was for services, up 1.4 percent, followed by a 0.6 percent increase for non-durable goods. Spending on durable goods, `` big ticket'' items expected to last three or more years, fell 0.6 percent. With income rising faster than spending, Americans saved more than in any month since October 1987. The personal savings rate _ savings as a percentage of after-tax income _ was 5.2 percent, up from 4.2 percent in September. Disposable, or after-tax income, was up 1.9 percent last month, also the largest increase in a year, after rising 0.6 percent a month earlier.
