<FIRST>u f AM-StatelyHomes Bjt   12-01 0716</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Stately Homes, Bjt,0742</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government to Stately Home Owners: `There's No Free Lunch'</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also on general news wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARCUS ELIASON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The British upper-classes got a tart reminder the other day of how far they've fallen on the ladder of national priorities. It came in a speech by <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON> <PERSON> Ridley </PERSON>, environment secretary in the Conservative government, and concerned one of the very pillars of British aristocracy _ the stately home. Addressing the <ORGANIZATION> Historic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Houses </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> on Nov. 22, <PERSON> Ridley </PERSON> delivered a blunt message on these lines: if you ca n't afford the upkeep of your stately home, do n't ask the government for help; sell it to the `` nouveaux riches.'' The speech, which brought ripples of reproach from the landed gentry, was another sign of how the old <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> has been transformed. The <ORGANIZATION> Conservative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, once topheavy with squires and knights of the shires, today is peopled with the likes of <PERSON> Ridley </PERSON>, a civil engineer, and Prime Minister <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON>, the daughter of a chemist and a grocer. Things have changed drastically since 1938, when <PERSON> Noel </PERSON> <PERSON> Coward </PERSON> wrote: `` The stately homes of <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> How beautiful they stand To prove the upper classes Still have the upper hand.'' The post-World War II <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> government, intent on fostering socialist egalitarianism, imposed massive taxation on inherited wealth, forcing many owners to turn their stately homes over to the public. The homes became museums, while the owners moved into small corners of the estate. By one estimate, the number of major stately homes occupied by one family shrank from 10,000 to 2,000. <PERSON> Ridley </PERSON> recalled the days when governments, to preserve historic mansions for the nation, had to pay `` simply to keep roofs on and walls standing.'' But after a decade of Thatcherism, he said, `` Things have changed. Everywhere we see the new prosperity. Millionaires abound and there are many more budding ones called yuppies.'' Yet he was still hearing `` cries from some quarters for more, rather than less state help.'' That, he said, was out. `` There have to be some opportunities for today's nouveaux riches, so I am not impressed by the case of the anciens pauvres,'' he said. Nor was he impressed by noble lineages. `` Many families who pride themselves on having always lived in a house in fact married into it, bought it or stole it at some point in their murky history, when they were robber barons, property speculators or simply won the pools.'' <PERSON> Ridley </PERSON>'s blunt talk drew some testy responses. Right-wing commentator <PERSON> Roger </PERSON> <PERSON> Scruton </PERSON> suggested that as the second son of noble family, <PERSON> Ridley </PERSON>, 59, suffered from the British affliction of `` younger son syndrome'' _ a resentment born of primogeniture, whereby the first-born inherits the title and estate, while the others must fend for themselves. In the conservative <ORGANIZATION> Daily </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telegraph </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Lees-Milne </PERSON> called <PERSON> Ridley </PERSON>'s remarks `` totally unwarranted,'' arguing that stately families were doing a service to conservation by staying on their land. <PERSON> Hugh </PERSON> <PERSON> Montgomery-Massingberd </PERSON>, author of a guide to British country houses, says the problem is not with the larger homes, which can easily be turned into money-spinning public attractions, but the smaller homes, whose owners are hard-pressed to survive. `` The families that are still in their homes have a lot of influence and do a lot of good,'' he said in an interview. They feel greater responsibility for their tenant farmers and hold unpaid public posts like high sheriff and justice of the peace. `` I wonder whether the nouveaux riches, who use these places as weekend pads to impress their friends, would be willing to take on these responsibilities,'' he said. Also, he said, the attraction of country homes is their valuable furnishings, historic collections that risk being broken up and sold off by new owners lacking a sense of heritage. <PERSON> Terence </PERSON> <PERSON> Empson </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> Historic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Houses </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> where <PERSON> Ridley </PERSON> spoke, said homeowners had already proved ingenious at fending for themselves, turning their estates into conference centers, safari parks and even `` war games parks'' for adventurous executives. <PERSON> Ridley </PERSON>'s exhortations might apply to smaller homes within commuting distance of the cities, he said in an interview. `` But if you have a historic home on a palatial scale deep in the countryside, I do n't see millionaire yuppies queuing round the block to buy it. The market just is n't there.''
</TEXT>
