<HEAD>Winston-Salem Merchants See Dollar Signs In RJR Nabisco Deal</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-RJR Nabisco, Bjt</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> WINSTON-SALEM </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.C. </LOCATION> -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- _ When $ 2 billion from the buyout of <ORGANIZATION> RJR </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nabisco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> hits <LOCATION> Winston-Salem </LOCATION>, the people who sell jewels, cars and houses for a living hope to be busy. Analysts estimate that 9,000 people in <LOCATION> Winston-Salem </LOCATION>, former headquarters of the food and tobacco giant, own $ 1 billion worth of stock in the company, and that local trusts, foundations and retirement plans own another $ 1 billion. The estimates are based on a stock price of $ 100 a share. The company was auctioned off Wednesday to buyout specialists <ORGANIZATION> Kohlberg </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kravis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Roberts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> in a deal worth about $ 109 a share to stockholders in cash and securities. When local shareholders receive their share of the proceeds, it could make for a very merry Christmas for area merchants. <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Winstead </PERSON>, the general manager of <ORGANIZATION> Hanes </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mall </ORGANIZATION>, said that unlike retailers in other parts of the country, merchants at his mall have seen strong sales so far in the Christmas shopping season. Money from the buyout could only make it better. `` The merchants of <LOCATION> Hanes </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mall </LOCATION>, as well as other retailers in this area, are prepared to serve with whatever the stockholders need,'' <PERSON> Winstead </PERSON> said. `` Do I sound reserved enough?'' <PERSON> Winstead </PERSON> said the people who have seen their stock climb by $ 37 a share over the past six weeks might well wish to make `` celebration-type purchases'' of luxury items when their checks arrive. At <ORGANIZATION> Windsor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jewelers </ORGANIZATION> in downtown <LOCATION> Winston-Salem </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Lois </PERSON> <PERSON> Simon </PERSON> said she has already noticed an influx of customers who do n't look like the usual clientele for expensive jewelry. `` These are definitely not typical of the clientele that would be pricing our emeralds and diamonds,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Simon </PERSON> said. She said she assumes the prospective customers are scouting out purchases they could make with the proceeds from the sale of their <ORGANIZATION> RJR </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nabisco </ORGANIZATION> stock. The company moved its headquarters to <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> last year but maintains the core of its tobacco operations here. <PERSON> Tim </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Cooper </PERSON>, sales manager at a Mercedes dealership, said he has n't yet seen any customers who are eager to put down their RJR profits on a new Mercedes. But he added: `` I hope we do see some increase in traffic due to that.'' Two local realtors _ <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Frye </PERSON> and <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> Hubbard </PERSON> _ said some <ORGANIZATION> RJR </ORGANIZATION> investors may put their proceeds into new homes. `` What I see happening is what anyone would see if you have a rich uncle die,'' <PERSON> Frye </PERSON> said. `` I think a lot of people will take awhile, but they'll eventually look at upgrading their living standards.'' But economists at two local universities said the windfall probably wo n't spawn a huge spending spree in <LOCATION> Winston-Salem </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Frey </PERSON>, an economics professor at <ORGANIZATION> Wake </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, said many investors _ and especially large institutions _ will probably just reinvest their money. `` Most people are n't going to confuse it with income,'' he said. `` They would say, ` These are assets that I worked to create, so I'm not going to go out and blow it on a vacation.' He said employees of subsidiary <ORGANIZATION> R.J. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reynolds </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tobacco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> who are worried about the future of their jobs will probably be careful about how they use the money from the sale of their company. `` Not all of that spending will take place immediately, and not all of it will take place in <LOCATION> Winston </LOCATION>,'' said <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Jud </PERSON>, a professor of finance at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Carolina </ORGANIZATION> at <LOCATION> Greensboro </LOCATION>.
