<HEAD>Analysts Expect Asset Auction, Less New Product Spending</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Some of the world's best-known food brands may ultimately be sold and spending on marketing and new product development may be cut as a result of the $ 24.5 billion buyout of <ORGANIZATION> RJR </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nabisco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, analysts said Thursday. But the analysts said they can not predict whether retail prices will go up or consumers will find it harder to locate their favorite snacks until it becomes clear who winds up with specific products. Many analysts expect the apparent winner in the buyout battle, a group led by the investment firm <ORGANIZATION> Kohlberg </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kravis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Roberts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, will be forced to sell chunks of the company to meet interest payments on the huge debt that will be incur in making the purchase. `` I've got to assume they will sell a lot of the foods operations,'' said <PERSON> Neal </PERSON> <PERSON> Kaplan </PERSON>, the food and tobacco analyst for the investment firm <ORGANIZATION> Interstate-Johnson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lane </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Charlotte </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.C </LOCATION>. He said <PERSON> Kohlberg </PERSON> <PERSON> Kravis </PERSON> probably would keep the tobacco company because of the strong cash flow it generated and then sell stock to the public later to raise money. Officials of <ORGANIZATION> Kohlberg </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kravis </ORGANIZATION> could not be reached for comment on their plans for <ORGANIZATION> RJR </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nabisco </ORGANIZATION>. A spokeswoman speaking on condition that she not be identified said the firm had said repeatedly it wanted `` to keep the company as intact as possible'' and avoid `` massive selling of all the food operations.'' But <PERSON> Kaplan </PERSON> and other analysts said the debt costs would make it all but certain that the new owners would be forced to sell some key operations, such as <PERSON> Nabisco </PERSON>'s cookie and cracker business, its candy, cereal and snack foods interests or its Del Monte canned vegetable and tropical fruits divisions. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Goldman </PERSON>, the food and tobacco analyst for <ORGANIZATION> Fahnestock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, estimated the new owners could get $ 8 billion for either the Nabisco foods business or the <ORGANIZATION> Reynolds </ORGANIZATION> tobacco business, $ 4 billion to $ 7 billion for <ORGANIZATION> Del </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Monte </ORGANIZATION> and $ 800 million to $ 1.2 billion for the Planters nuts and Life Savers candy business. The list of buyers who analysts cite as potential buyers of parts of the Nabisco operations include the biggest names in consumer products _ <ORGANIZATION> Procter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gamble </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Ralston-Purina </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Quaker </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oats </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Pepsico </ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION> Borden </LOCATION>. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Maxwell </PERSON>, food and tobacco analyst for <ORGANIZATION> Wheat </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Richmond </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, said <ORGANIZATION> Procter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gamble </ORGANIZATION>, for instance, might be keenly interested in <PERSON> Nabisco </PERSON>'s ready-to-eat cookie business. <PERSON> Nabisco </PERSON>'s cookie brands include Oreo, Chips Ahoy and <PERSON> Fig </PERSON> <PERSON> Newton </PERSON> and it also owns Ritz crackers. He said <PERSON> Ralston </PERSON> or Quaker might be interested in adding <PERSON> Nabisco </PERSON>'s Shredded Wheat to their line of cereals, while <ORGANIZATION> Pepsico </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> Borden </PERSON> might want Planters nuts to expand their own snack food operations Whether or not major assets are sold, <ORGANIZATION> Goldman </ORGANIZATION> said, the new owners will have to cut corners to meet debt payments. `` You could see some modest reductions in advertising and other marketing tools such as couponing and consumer promotions,'' he said. <ORGANIZATION> RJR </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nabisco </ORGANIZATION> was for fifth largest national advertiser in 1987, spending nearly $ 840 million in support of both its food and tobacco businesses last year, according to the trade journal Advertising Age. <ORGANIZATION> Goldman </ORGANIZATION> expects a sharp decline in new product introductions because `` you just do n't have the latitude for loss that you had as an ongoing company.'' <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Friedman </PERSON>, editor of <PERSON> Gorman </PERSON>'s New Product News, said less than 1 percent of the 11,000 new food and drug products this year will produce the level of national sales that major companies generally consider a success. <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> Stibel </PERSON>, a partner in the marketing firm <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> England </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Consulting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Westport </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Conn. </LOCATION>, said the prospects for any given line of food products rests entirely with the group that ultimately ends up owning them. Companies that buy a product line to expand their existing share of markets generally spend heavily to promote them and may raise prices, he said. But companies that buy a product line in hopes of selling it later for a profit may be more apt to cut promotional spending and try to live off the line's reputation as long as possible, he said. The fallout from the <ORGANIZATION> RJR </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nabisco </ORGANIZATION> buyout would no necessarily be limited to the food operations, <ORGANIZATION> Fahnestock </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Goldman </ORGANIZATION> said. He said the buyout could mean an early end to <ORGANIZATION> RJR </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nabisco </ORGANIZATION>'s two-month test of its smokeless cigarette, Premier, which delivers nicotine like a cigarette without much of the smoke `` The Premier appeared to be a dead product to begin with. Consumer aceptanmce of the product has been dismal. Health authorities have been rallying against it,'' <PERSON> Goldman </PERSON> said. He said the new owners might decide to spare themselves the legal costs that might be needed to defend the product against legal challenges. `` Premier will become the Edsel of 1988,'' he predicted, referring to the automobile that proved a costly failure.
