UPDATE with closing stock price in 2nd graf; picks up 3rd graf pvs,
The charge ....</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telephone </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telegraph </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> said Thursday it will post the first annual loss in its 103-year history as a result of a $ 6.7 billion pre-tax charge that covers the costs of scrapping outdated equipment and moving, retiring or laying off 16,000 employees. Wall Street saw the giant charge as a sign that <ORGANIZATION> AT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> T </ORGANIZATION> was moving aggressively to cut costs and install a new digital network to meet the competition. The stock was fairly stable, falling 50 cents to $ 29.37 -LCB- a share in consolidated <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> trading. The charge will not affect <ORGANIZATION> AT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; T's cash flow, its ability to pay dividends or the money available for investment. `` This reflects the adjustment of going from a regulated marketplace to a competitive marketplace,'' said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Morris </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON>, a San Francisco-based analyst for <ORGANIZATION> Goldman </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sachs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> AT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; T said the charge would reduce its after-tax profits by $ 3.9 billion That makes it likely that the company will lose about $ 1.6 billion in all of 1988 and $ 3.3 billion in the fourth quarter alone. The only larger quarterly losses in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> history were <ORGANIZATION> AT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; T's own $ 4.87 billion loss in the fourth quarter of 1983, which involved a charge to prepare for the Bell System breakup, and <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>'s $ 4.76 billion loss in the fourth quarter of 1987 stemming from its legal fight with <ORGANIZATION> Pennzoil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co </ORGANIZATION> Long-distance phone companies have been moving aggressively to replace their old-fashioned analog equipment with new digital equipment that provides higher quality and is better suited to custom services and transmission of computer data. The bulk of the charge, $ 5.0 billion, is to reflect on the books the lower value of outdated analog network equipment. The remaining $ 1.7 billion is for the costs of removing the outdated equipment, writedowns in the value of related equipment, and reductions in employment. <ORGANIZATION> AT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> T </ORGANIZATION> said it would reduce the number of its network employees by 10,000 and the number of its operators by 6,000 over the next few years. <ORGANIZATION> AT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; T does not yet know how many of the employees will be given jobs elsewhere in the company because that depends on the company's growth, spokeswoman <PERSON> LuAnn </PERSON> <PERSON> Gardner </PERSON> said The Communications Workers of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, the union representing 135,000 <ORGANIZATION> AT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; T workers, issued a statement saying non-management employees have suffered the loss of 78,500 jobs since 1984 while management ranks have risen by 13,600. `` This company just has not bitten the bullet _ it has not come out of its ` monopoly cocoon' levels of management,'' the union said. <ORGANIZATION> AT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; T spokesman <PERSON> Burke </PERSON> <PERSON> Stinson </PERSON> responded that the company had to hire white-collar workers because of its new thrusts into computers and foreign markets. But he said `` we're not blind to the fact'' that staff jobs need to be cut. <ORGANIZATION> AT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; T has a freeze on hiring over most of the company. That gives the displaced employees a better chance to find work elsewhere within the company than if they had to face competition from new hires. Plans to reduce 3,000 of the network jobs and all 6,000 of the operator service jobs had already been announced to employees, <ORGANIZATION> AT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; T said. The company is setting aside $ 400 million to cover the cost of redeploying them or giving them payments or incentives related to separation from the company by retirement or resignation. The job cuts are possible because improvements in the network reduce the need for maintenance, engineering, service, order processing and call handling. Operators at new stations are able to handle 25 percent more calls per hour, the company said. <ORGANIZATION> AT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; T has switched over to a digital network far more rapidly than it had previously planned. The company predicted early in 1987 that it would take until the year 2010 to have an all-digital network. By the end of 1987 it said it could do the job by 1991. On Thursday, it said it could do the job by the end of next year. <ORGANIZATION> MCI </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> US </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sprint </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, the No. 2 and No. 3 competitors in long distance, have also moved rapidly to put in digital networks and have taken big charges to write down the book value of their outdated analog equipment. Executives of <ORGANIZATION> AT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; T had said in October that writedowns in the fourth quarter could be substantial. By taking the pain of the writedown all at once, <ORGANIZATION> AT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; T no longer has to lower its quarterly profits to reflect the costs of depreciating the older equipment. `` We view this as very positive news,'' Ms. <PERSON> Gardner </PERSON> said. `` Our network will continue to be the best out there.'' AT & amp; T took a $ 10 billion pre-tax charge at the end of 1983 to prepare for the divestiture of its local telephone companies. It also took pre-tax charges of $ 200 million in 1985 and $ 3.2 billion at the end of 1986. <ORGANIZATION> AT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; T has reduced employment by 64,000 since the breakup of the Bell System on Jan. 1, 1984. It has about 310,000 employees now, and that could drop to below 300,000 over the next three to five years, Ms. <PERSON> Gardner </PERSON> said. As large as the job cuts are, securities analysts said they could be even larger. `` They have grossly too many people. At the time of divestiture, a lot of people were unloaded onto them,'' said <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> McCabe </PERSON>, an analyst at <ORGANIZATION> Nomura </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION>. He said the cuts have occu