<HEAD>Wheat Futures Slide on Absence of Soviet Wheat Purchase</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Wheat futures prices fell sharply Thursday on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION>, reflecting disappointment that the new grain deal with the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> had not yet produced a wheat transaction, analysts said. Other grain futures closed mostly lower and soybeans posted substantial losses on fears of a wet weekend in the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> soybean belt. On other markets, sugar futures rose sharply; precious metals declined; energy futures rallied; livestock and meat futures were higher; and stock-index futures advanced. Many wheat traders had expected the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> to offer the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> a large amount of subsidized <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> wheat under the Export Enhancement Program within days of Monday's signing of a 27-month grain agreement. The absence of such an offer spawned speculation Thursday that the superpowers were still haggling over price and that any purchases would not be immediately forthcoming, said <PERSON> Dale </PERSON> <PERSON> Gustafson </PERSON>, a grain market analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Burnham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lambert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. `` The trade is beginning to believe that we may not see the wheat business coming in December, and maybe not until well after that,'' he said. The new grain agreement calls for the Soviets to purchase 4 million metric tons of wheat, 4 million tons of corn and 1 million tons of their choice in both the current year, which began Oct. 1, and the following year. Conflicting forecasts for the weekend weather in <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION>, where soybean planting is under way, prompted a sell-off in the soybean pit, analysts said. If the dry weather that has marked the early part of the planting period persists into the growing season, South American forecasts could lend a fair amount of volatility to the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> futures market, <PERSON> Gustafson </PERSON> said. Wheat settled 3 cents to 10 \ cents lower with the contract for delivery in December at $ 4.16 a bushel; corn was 4 cents lower to -RCB- cent higher with December at $ 2.57 \ a bushel; oats were 3 -LCB- cents to 5 cents lower with December at $ 1.91 a bushel; soybeans were 5 -LCB- cents to 8 -LCB- cents lower with January at $ 7.58 a Sugar futures made strong gains on <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s Coffee, <ORGANIZATION> Sugar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Cocoa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> in a rally linked to bullish technical signals and indications that world production may fall short of consumption this year, leading to a reduction in stockpiles. At this point, though, `` there appears to be plenty of physical sugar available, so it seems to be just a speculative rally,'' said <PERSON> Erik </PERSON> <PERSON> Dunlaevy </PERSON>, sugar market analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Balfour </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Maclaine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. Sugar settled .31 cent to .49 cent higher with the active March contract at 11.44 cents a pound, the highest price for March delivery since July 25. Platinum prices dipped amid profit-taking on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> following Wednesday's stunning advance of nearly $ 25 a troy ounce. A strengthening of the dollar also contributed to lower precious-metals prices, as did jitters prior to Friday's release of November unemployment figures. `` That always makes traders uneasy,'' said <PERSON> Bette </PERSON> <PERSON> Raptopoulos </PERSON>, metals analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Prudential-Bache </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. Platinum settled $ 7.80 to $ 13.80 lower with January at $ 600.90 a troy ounce. On <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s Commodity Exchange, gold settled 90 cents to $ 1.10 lower with December at $ 423.90 a troy ounce; silver was 4 cents to 5.1 cents lower with December at $ 6.096 a troy ounce. Energy futures prices rose on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> in technically-inspired trading in the absence of new supply-demand developments, analysts said. West Texas Intermediate crude oil was 10 cents to 29 cents higher with January at $ 15.61 a barrel; heating oil was .17 cent to .94 cent higher with January at 49.18 cents a gallon; unleaded gasoline was .25 cent lower to .83 cent higher with January at 45.98 cents a gallon. Cattle futures firmed in a rebound from three consecutive days of lower prices on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. `` People know the long-term outlook is bullish,'' said <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Levitt </PERSON>, senior livestock analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lehman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hutton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. Expectations for a mid-December slowdown in hog slaughters boosted pork futures, he said. Live cattle settled .18 cent to .35 cent higher with December at 72.50 cents a pound; feed