<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Stock prices drifted lower Thursday in a sluggish session marked by worries that interest rates may be headed higher. Analysts said many investors appeared to prefer standing aside in advance of the November employment report due Friday which could provide some indication of whether the economy is moderating or overheating. `` Right now everybody is sitting back waiting for the employment figures,'' said <PERSON> Alfred </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Goldman </PERSON>, an analyst for the brokerage <ORGANIZATION> A.G. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Edwards </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sons </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Louis </LOCATION>. `` Nobody has any conviction one way or the other.'' The Dow Jones average of 30 industrial stocks, up 12.98 points on Wednesday and nearly 40 points over the past three sessions, lost 12.63 to close at 2,101.88. Declining issues outnumbered gainers by about 8-to-7 in nationwide trading of <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> Exchange-listed stocks, with 680 issues up, 805 down and 486 unchanged. Volume on the floor of the <ORGANIZATION> NYSE </ORGANIZATION> came to 129.38 million shares, down from 157.81 million in the previous session. Nationwide, consolidated volume in NYSE-listed issues, including trading at regional exchanges and on the over-the-counter market, totaled 155.12 million shares. Analysts said traders were worried that employment growth in November would indicate faster-than-expected expansion in the economy. If the economy were found to be expanding too quickly, many analysts fear that the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> may feel compelled to push interest rates higher to slow it down and restrain inflation. Higher rates make short-term fixed-income investments more competitive with the uncertain returns on stocks. Three-month <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> bills, for instance, are yielding about 8.10 percent. <PERSON> Goldman </PERSON> said most economists expect payroll growth of between 225,000 and 250,000 in November. A number significantly higher than that, he said, `` would mean the economy is in fact overheating and the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> is going to have to step on the monetary brakes more heavily than they have already.'' But there is considerable uncertainty about how fast the economy is expanding. Stocks rallied earlier this week on indications that the economy may be growing at a more moderate pace. In a new report Thursday, the government said its chief forecasting gauge of future economic activity edged up a sluggish 0.1 percent in October after falling by a revised 0.3 percent in September. <ORGANIZATION> RJR </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nabisco </ORGANIZATION> fell 1 \ to 91 -RCB- and was the most active stock on the <ORGANIZATION> NYSE </ORGANIZATION> The company said late Wednesday it had accepted an offer of $ 109 a share in cash and securities from buyout specialist <ORGANIZATION> Kohlberg </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kravis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Roberts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, spurning a competing offer from a management group. <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telephone </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Telegraph </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> was also active. It fell -LCB- to 29 -RRB- after saying it will take a $ 6.7 billion charge against its fourth-quarter earnings to cover expenses related to getting rid of outdated telephone equipment. General Cinema climbed 2 to 23 ~ after announcing its plann