<HEAD>Standard &amp; Poor's Places Four Insurance Companies on Creditwatch</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Standard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Poor </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> said Thursday it was re-evaluating its credit ratings of four insurance companies following the passage of <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>'s Proposition 103. <ORGANIZATION> Standard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Poor's said it was placing <ORGANIZATION> Allstate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Farmers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, Fireman's Fund and <ORGANIZATION> Safeco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> on its `` Creditwatch'' list with negative implications. That means <ORGANIZATION> Standard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Poor's might downgrade the ratings of the four insurers. The firm lowers credit ratings, which are a factor in determining how much a company must pay to borrow money in the bond markets, when it determines the company's ability to raise the money for repaying its debt has been affected. Proposition 103, which <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> voters approved Nov. 8, requires that rates for motor vehicle, homeowner and other property and casualty insurance be rolled back to November 1987 levels and then reduced 20 percent and frozen until November 1989. Insurers can request exemptions, but they are to be granted only if the companies show a `` substantial threat of insolvency'' would result from the rate cuts. Among the measure's other provisions is a requirement that, beginning in November 1989, the state insurance commissioner approve all rate increases. Any increases that are `` excessive, inadequate or unfairly discriminatory'' will be prohibited. A number of insurance companies have filed suit in the <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> to challenge the constitutionality of Proposition 103, and many insurers have restricted or eliminated their <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> coverage. The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> has blocked enforcement of the 20 percent rate reduction and other provisions while the suit is under consideration.
